INSERT INTO `core_lessonsection` VALUES (1170,1,'Overview','text','Budgeting is often misunderstood as a restriction, but it is actually a tool for freedom. It is simply a plan for your money that tells it where to go before you spend it, rather than wondering where it went. Instead of limiting your fun, a budget gives you permission to spend without guilt.\n\nThis simple habit turns financial guesswork into a clear picture of your reality. It highlights exactly how much money is coming in compared to how much is going out. With this clarity, you can make confident choices and finally feel in control of your wallet.',NULL,NULL,2,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.056930',NULL),(1171,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/DEsAQhLBIHU',NULL,2,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.057355',NULL),(1172,3,'Key Concepts','text','At its core, a budget is about balancing two main numbers: your income and your expenses. Your income is what actually hits your bank account, while expenses include everything from rent to that morning coffee. Seeing these side-by-side helps you immediately spot where your money might be leaking.\n\nMany people realize they are spending more than they earn only after writing it down. This awareness allows you to separate your essential needs from your non-essential wants. Once you see the difference, you can prioritize spending on things that truly matter to your future.',NULL,NULL,2,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.057806',NULL),(1173,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 164}',2,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.058249',NULL),(1174,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','<p>The best way to start is to look at your past behavior rather than guessing dthe future. Action: Log into your banking app and write down your last seven days of spending in broad categories like food, travel, and fun. Don\'t judge yourself; just observe the numbers. Once you have the list, calculate your total spend for the week versus your income. Metric: Identify the gap (positive or negative) between what came in and what went out. Question: What one small change, like making coffee at home once, could free up at least £10 next week?</p>','','{}',2,NULL,1,'2025-12-20 16:08:45.098513',221),(1175,1,'Overview','text','The primary benefit of budgeting is the mental clarity and peace of mind it provides. When you don\'t track your money, every purchase can feel like a gamble that might result in a declined card. A budget removes this low-level anxiety by defining your safe spending limits clearly.\n\nIt also acts as an early warning system for your overall financial health. You will notice if your spending is outpacing your income long before you run into serious debt. This gives you the chance to adjust course while the problems are still small and manageable.',NULL,NULL,3,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.345873',NULL),(1176,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/X-UdOZZ5oIc',NULL,3,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.346361',NULL),(1177,3,'Key Concepts','text','Budgeting protects you from the unexpected by helping you build an emergency fund. By assigning a job to every pound, you can set aside money specifically for car repairs or medical bills. This turns what would be a financial disaster into a minor inconvenience.\n\nFurthermore, budgeting helps you stop wasting money on things you don\'t actually value. It highlights subscriptions you forgot about or habits that don\'t bring you joy. You can then redirect that cash toward goals that actually excite you, like a holiday or a new home.',NULL,NULL,3,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.346907',NULL),(1178,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 165, \"expected_value\": 900}',3,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.347318',NULL),(1179,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','The first version of your budget won’t be perfect, so expect to adjust it as you go. Action: List your three biggest expense categories from last month and circle the one that surprises you most. Small improvements each week compound into meaningful progress over time.\n\nMetric: Calculate how much you would save in a year if you cut that circled category by just 10%. Question: Which daily habit gives the biggest return on investment if you reduce it slightly?',NULL,NULL,3,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.347929',NULL),(1180,1,'Overview','text','Money is just a tool, and a budget is the manual for using it to build the life you want. Without clear goals, it is easy to drift and spend money on things that don\'t actually make you happy. Goals give your budget a sense of purpose and provide the motivation to stick with it.\n\nThink of your financial goals as the destination on a road map. Whether you want to pay off a credit card or save for a dream holiday, the budget is the route you take to get there. When you have a clear \"why,\" saying no to impulse buys becomes much easier.',NULL,NULL,4,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.723082',NULL),(1181,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/xjWEqr_Dkq0',NULL,4,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.723981',NULL),(1182,3,'Key Concepts','text','To be effective, categorize your goals by time: short-term (1–3 months), medium-term (3–12 months), and long-term (1+ years). Start small and specific so you can measure your progress quickly and feel a sense of achievement. Success with small goals builds the confidence needed for bigger ones.\n\nUse the SMART framework: ensure your goals are Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound. Instead of saying \"I want to save money,\" say \"I will save £500 for a laptop by December.\" This precision forces your brain to take the goal seriously.',NULL,NULL,4,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.724705',NULL),(1183,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Learn how to set short-term and long-term financial goals that align with your overall financial objectives.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Setting Financial Goals\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 166, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',4,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.725730',NULL),(1184,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down one short-term goal you can reasonably fund within this month. Metric: Divide the total cost of the goal by the number of weeks left in the month to see your weekly target. Writing it down makes it real and increases the likelihood of success.\n\nQuestion: What is one obstacle that could derail you from hitting this goal, and how will you handle it? Identifying the roadblock before you hit it is the key to staying on track.',NULL,NULL,4,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.726532',NULL),(1185,1,'Overview','text','Creating a budget is simpler than it sounds; start by listing your net income and your average monthly expenses. Net income is the money that actually hits your bank account after taxes and deductions. Next, group your costs into fixed categories like rent and variable ones like groceries.\n\nOnce you have the data, you can see the trade-offs clearly and make decisions. If your expenses are higher than your income, you know you need to cut back or earn more. Giving every pound a specific job ensures you don\'t accidentally overspend.',NULL,NULL,5,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.970949',NULL),(1186,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/b9iwISYBI-g',NULL,5,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.971978',NULL),(1187,3,'Key Concepts','text','A popular method to structure your budget is the 50/30/20 rule. Allocate 50% of your income to Needs (essentials), 30% to Wants (lifestyle), and 20% to Savings or Debt repayment. This framework is flexible and prevents you from feeling deprived while still securing your future.\n\nDraft a simple plan for the next month using realistic numbers based on your past spending. Don\'t try to be perfect immediately; aim for a plan that is \"good enough\" to start. Keep a small financial buffer in your plan for unexpected costs so they don\'t break your budget.',NULL,NULL,5,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.972499',NULL),(1188,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 167}',5,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.972993',NULL),(1189,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Create a one-month budget draft with three simple categories (Needs, Wants, Savings/Debt). Metric: Calculate the difference between your planned spending and your actual income to ensure you aren\'t in the red. A balanced budget should equal zero or leave a surplus.\n\nQuestion: Which category most often runs over budget for you, and why? Identifying the \"problem child\" category is the first step to fixing it in next month\'s plan.',NULL,NULL,5,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:42.973593',NULL),(1190,1,'Overview','text','A budget is only a plan, but tracking your spending is the reality check that makes it work. You must record your expenses as they happen to see if you are actually following the plan you made. This feedback loop is essential for spotting where you might be overspending.\n\nTracking turns your financial life into a weekly scorecard that helps you improve. It reveals hidden habits, like that daily snack that adds up to hundreds a year. By seeing the data, you can make micro-adjustments that save you money without feeling painful.',NULL,NULL,6,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.228528',NULL),(1191,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/xzTrAYn3iyk',NULL,6,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.229041',NULL),(1192,3,'Key Concepts','text','Pick a simple method you’ll actually use, whether it is a notes app, a spreadsheet, or a dedicated finance app. The best tool is the one that you can stick with consistently over the long term. Log spending soon after it happens so nothing gets lost or forgotten.\n\nReview your tracking weekly to catch any issues before the month is over. If you overspent on dining out this week, you can cook at home next week to balance it out. This agility keeps you on track toward your goals without needing to restart every month.',NULL,NULL,6,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.229517',NULL),(1193,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 168}',6,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.230005',NULL),(1194,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Commit to tracking every single purchase for the next seven days, no matter how small. Metric: Compare your total spend at the end of the week against the budget you set in the previous lesson. Seeing the variance is the most powerful lesson in personal finance.\n\nQuestion: What one recurring expense could you reduce by 10% without hurting your quality of life? Often, we pay for convenience or habit rather than value, and tracking exposes this immediately.',NULL,NULL,6,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.230505',NULL),(1195,1,'Overview','text','Credit is essentially a relationship built on trust between you and a lender. It is the ability to borrow money or access goods now with the promise that you will pay for them later. Instead of carrying stacks of cash, you use your reputation to make purchases, agreeing to repay the amount—usually with a little extra called interest.\n\nThink of credit as a tool that extends your financial reach beyond what is currently in your bank account. It is not \"free money,\" but rather a service that you pay for over time. When used responsibly, it opens doors to buying a home or a car; when used poorly, it can lock those doors shut.',NULL,NULL,7,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.502667',NULL),(1196,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/hnq-TGXFoZw',NULL,7,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.503271',NULL),(1197,3,'Key Concepts','text','The credit system relies on your history as a borrower to predict your future behavior. Every time you pay a bill on time or miss a payment, it gets recorded in a file that lenders review. If you prove you are reliable, lenders are happy to give you more money at lower costs because they trust you will pay it back.\n\nConversely, if you break that trust by missing payments, borrowing becomes difficult and expensive. This history forms your \"creditworthiness,\" which acts like a financial CV. Lenders use this CV to decide if you are a safe bet or a risky investment before they hand over any cash.',NULL,NULL,7,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.504041',NULL),(1198,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 169}',7,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.504537',NULL),(1199,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Log into your bank account and identify if you have any overdraft facility or credit products already active. Metric: Check the interest rate (APR) associated with that borrowing to understand the cost of using it. Knowledge is power, and knowing the price of your debt is the first step to mastering it.\n\nQuestion: If you borrowed £100 today and had to pay back £120 next month, would that purchase still be worth it? Asking this simple question before swiping your card can save you from high-interest traps. Building a habit of pausing before borrowing ensures you only use credit when it truly benefits you.',NULL,NULL,7,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.504984',NULL),(1200,1,'Overview','text','Not all credit is created equal, and understanding the different types is crucial for financial success. The two main categories you will encounter are \"revolving credit\" and \"installment credit.\" Revolving credit, like a credit card, lets you borrow up to a limit, pay it back, and borrow again endlessly.\n\nInstallment credit, on the other hand, is for a fixed amount of money borrowed for a specific purpose. You receive the money in one lump sum—like a car loan or student loan—and pay it back in equal monthly chunks over a set period. Once the loan is paid off, the account is closed.',NULL,NULL,8,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.778210',NULL),(1201,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/15PUXzW8v4s',NULL,8,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.778692',NULL),(1202,3,'Key Concepts','text','Another key distinction is between \"secured\" and \"unsecured\" debt. Secured loans require collateral, meaning you must pledge an asset like your house or car that the lender can take if you fail to pay. Because the lender has this safety net, these loans often come with lower interest rates.\n\nUnsecured loans, such as most personal loans and credit cards, do not require any physical collateral. Since the lender is taking a bigger risk by trusting just your promise, they typically charge higher interest rates. Knowing which type you are signing up for helps you assess the risks involved.',NULL,NULL,8,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.779123',NULL),(1203,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 170, \"expected_value\": 900}',8,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.779566',NULL),(1204,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Look at your current debts (or potential future ones) and categorize them as revolving or installment. Metric: Note which debts have a fixed end date and which ones could theoretically last forever if you only pay the minimum. This highlights which debts require more disciplined management.\n\nQuestion: Why might a credit card be more dangerous than a car loan for an impulsive spender? Recognizing that revolving credit requires constant self-discipline can help you avoid the trap of perpetual debt. Choose the credit type that matches your personality and financial goals.',NULL,NULL,8,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:43.779980',NULL),(1205,1,'Overview','text','Your credit score is a three-digit number that acts as a grade for your financial reliability. It typically ranges from 300 to 850, and a higher score signals to lenders that you are a low-risk borrower. This single number can determine whether you get approved for an apartment, a loan, or even a smartphone contract.\n\nThink of it as a financial passport that grants you access to better opportunities and lower prices. Lenders, landlords, and insurers all peek at this score to judge how responsible you are with money. Protecting this number is one of the most important things you can do for your financial future.',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.022454',NULL),(1206,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/1w_SM2RXTWA',NULL,9,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.023445',NULL),(1207,3,'Key Concepts','text','Several factors make up your score, but the most impactful one is your payment history. Paying your bills on time, every single time, accounts for roughly 35% of your score, making consistency the golden rule. Even one missed payment can cause your score to drop significantly, so automation is your friend.\n\nThe second biggest factor is credit utilization, which is how much of your available credit limit you are currently using. Experts recommend keeping this below 30%—so if you have a £1,000 limit, try not to carry a balance over £300. Maxing out your cards makes you look desperate for cash, which lowers your score.',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.023989',NULL),(1208,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Discover how credit scores are calculated, what affects them, and how to improve your score.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Understanding Credit Scores\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 171, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',9,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.024524',NULL),(1209,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check your credit score for free using a service like Experian, Credit Karma, or your banking app. Metric: Identify your current score band (e.g., Fair, Good, Excellent) and see how far you are from the next level up. Knowing your starting point is essential for tracking progress.\n\nQuestion: What is one bill you could put on autopay right now to ensure you never miss a due date? establishing this safety net guarantees you maximize the \'payment history\' portion of your score. Small systematic changes today lead to a pristine credit score tomorrow.',NULL,NULL,9,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.024979',NULL),(1210,1,'Overview','text','Building credit from scratch can feel like a catch-22: you need credit to get credit. The best way to start is often with a \"secured credit card,\" where you put down a cash deposit that acts as your credit limit. This eliminates the risk for the lender while allowing you to build a history of on-time payments.\n\nAnother effective strategy is to become an \"authorized user\" on a family member\'s credit card. If they have a long history of good payments, their positive habits get reported on your credit file as well. This \"piggybacking\" method can give your score a quick boost without you needing to take out a loan yourself.',NULL,NULL,10,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.373430',NULL),(1211,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/ncmiu_STQE8',NULL,10,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.374023',NULL),(1212,3,'Key Concepts','text','Consistency is the secret ingredient to building a strong credit profile over time. Use your credit card for small, regular purchases like a Netflix subscription or a weekly coffee, and pay it off in full every month. You do not need to carry a balance or pay interest to build credit; you just need to show activity.\n\nAvoid applying for too many credit cards at once, as this can make you look risky to lenders. Each application triggers a \"hard inquiry\" that temporarily dips your score, so pace yourself. Aim to open accounts only when you truly need them and plan to use them responsibly.',NULL,NULL,10,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.374577',NULL),(1213,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 172}',10,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.375066',NULL),(1214,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Research one beginner-friendly credit building tool, such as a secured card or a credit-builder loan. Metric: Compare the annual fees and benefits of two different options to find the best fit for your wallet. Choosing the right tool prevents you from paying unnecessary fees while you build your score.\n\nQuestion: Can you commit to paying off your full balance every Friday to keep your utilization low? By treating your credit card like a debit card, you gain all the credit-building benefits without the risk of debt. It is about proving you can handle the responsibility.',NULL,NULL,10,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.375710',NULL),(1215,1,'Overview','text','Debt is not a life sentence; it is a mathematical problem with a solution. The first step to managing it is to stop the bleeding by halting any new borrowing immediately. You must face the numbers head-on by listing every single debt, its interest rate, and the minimum payment required.\n\nTwo popular strategies for paying off debt are the \"Snowball\" and \"Avalanche\" methods. The Snowball method focuses on psychology by paying off the smallest balance first to get a quick win. The Avalanche method focuses on math by attacking the debt with the highest interest rate first to save money in the long run.',NULL,NULL,11,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.623878',NULL),(1216,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/pftx9Jx6N1Q',NULL,11,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.624436',NULL),(1217,3,'Key Concepts','text','If you are feeling overwhelmed, debt consolidation might be a useful tool to simplify your life. This involves taking out one new loan to pay off multiple smaller debts, leaving you with just one single monthly payment. This can often lower your interest rate and reduce the mental load of tracking different due dates.\n\nHowever, consolidation only works if you have fixed the spending habits that got you into debt in the first place. Without a budget and a change in behavior, you risk running up the credit cards again while still owing the consolidation loan. It is a powerful tool, but it must be paired with discipline.',NULL,NULL,11,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.624993',NULL),(1218,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 173}',11,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.625460',NULL),(1219,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Choose your fighter: decide whether the Snowball (motivation) or Avalanche (math) method suits your personality better. Metric: Calculate the \"freedom date\"—the month and year you will be debt-free if you stick to your chosen plan. having a specific target date turns a vague wish into a concrete timeline.\n\nQuestion: What sacrifices are you willing to make for the next 6 months to speed up that freedom date? Whether it is cooking at home or cancelling streaming services, short-term pain leads to long-term gain. Your future self will thank you for the effort you put in today.',NULL,NULL,11,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.625966',NULL),(1220,1,'Overview','text','Investing is not about getting rich quick; it is about preserving and growing your purchasing power over time. If you keep your savings in cash under a mattress, inflation will slowly eat away its value, meaning you can buy less with it every year. Investing puts your money to work so that it grows faster than the cost of living rises.\n\nMany people confuse investing with gambling, but there is a distinct difference in strategy and mindset. Gambling relies on luck and often has a negative expected return, while investing relies on time, data, and the growth of the economy. The goal is to build a reliable engine for wealth that runs in the background of your life.',NULL,NULL,12,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.995456',NULL),(1221,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/J7dJ_tN1q1E',NULL,12,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.995924',NULL),(1222,3,'Key Concepts','text','The most powerful force in investing is \'compound interest,\' which Einstein reportedly called the eighth wonder of the world. This is the snowball effect where you earn interest on your original money, and then earn interest on that interest the following year. Over long periods, this exponential growth can turn modest monthly contributions into a massive nest egg.\n\nStarting early is more important than starting big because time is the primary fuel for compounding. Investing £50 a month in your 20s can often result in more wealth at retirement than investing £200 a month starting in your 40s. The best time to plant a tree was 20 years ago; the second best time is today.',NULL,NULL,12,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.996345',NULL),(1223,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 174}',12,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.996787',NULL),(1224,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Use an online \'Compound Interest Calculator\' to simulate saving £100 a month for 30 years at 7% return. Metric: Note the difference between the \'Total Contributions\' (what you put in) and the \'Future Value\' (what you end up with). Question: Are you willing to sacrifice a small luxury today for that kind of growth tomorrow?',NULL,NULL,12,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:44.997198',NULL),(1225,1,'Overview','text','The investment world is divided into \'asset classes,\' with the two most common being stocks (equities) and bonds (fixed income). When you buy a stock, you are buying a tiny piece of ownership in a company, meaning you share in its profits and its failures. Stocks generally offer higher growth potential but come with a rockier ride.\n\nBonds, on the other hand, are essentially a loan you give to a government or company in exchange for regular interest payments. They are generally safer and more stable than stocks, acting as a cushion for your portfolio during rough market times. However, their returns are usually lower, so they are often used to preserve wealth rather than build it aggressively.',NULL,NULL,13,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.267199',NULL),(1226,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/zUUEv87kHVI',NULL,13,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.267659',NULL),(1227,3,'Key Concepts','text','Beyond stocks and bonds, there are \'Funds\' like Mutual Funds or ETFs (Exchange Traded Funds). These allow you to buy a basket of hundreds of stocks or bonds in a single click, instantly spreading your risk. Instead of trying to pick the one winning needle in the haystack, you simply buy the whole haystack.\n\nAlternative investments include real estate, commodities like gold, and newer digital assets like cryptocurrency. These can provide diversification because they often move differently than the stock market. However, they can also be complex and volatile, so they typically make up a smaller portion of a beginner\'s portfolio.',NULL,NULL,13,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.268136',NULL),(1228,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 175, \"expected_value\": 900}',13,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.268718',NULL),(1229,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Search for the ticker symbol of a popular S&P 500 ETF (like VOO or SPY). Metric: Look at its \'5-year return\' to see how the general stock market has performed recently. Question: Do you prefer the safety of a bond or the growth potential of a stock right now?',NULL,NULL,13,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.269220',NULL),(1230,1,'Overview','text','In finance, risk and reward are joined at the hip; you generally cannot have high returns without accepting high risk. Risk is the possibility that you will lose money or that your investment will grow slower than expected. Safe investments like savings accounts pay little interest because there is almost zero risk of loss.\n\nHigh-risk investments, like individual tech stocks or crypto, offer the chance of doubling your money but also the chance of losing half of it. Understanding your personal \'risk tolerance\'—how much money you can lose without losing sleep—is crucial. Investing is as much about psychology as it is about math.',NULL,NULL,14,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.651043',NULL),(1231,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/BYrF64NqQ1I',NULL,14,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.651528',NULL),(1232,3,'Key Concepts','text','Your \'time horizon\' is the most important factor in determining how much risk you should take. If you need the money in 2 years for a house deposit, you should avoid volatile stocks because the market could crash just when you need to sell. You don\'t have time to wait for a recovery.\n\nHowever, if you are investing for retirement in 30 years, you can afford to take more risk. You have time to ride out the market\'s ups and downs, allowing you to capture higher long-term growth. Short-term volatility is just noise to a long-term investor.',NULL,NULL,14,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.652068',NULL),(1233,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Learn the relationship between risk and reward in investing, and how to assess your risk tolerance.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Risk and Reward\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 176, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',14,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.652660',NULL),(1234,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Rate your risk tolerance on a scale of 1 (terrified of loss) to 10 (love the thrill). Metric: How would you feel if your portfolio dropped 20% tomorrow—would you buy more or panic sell? Question: Does your current investment strategy match that feeling?',NULL,NULL,14,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.653078',NULL),(1235,1,'Overview','text','Diversification is often called the \'only free lunch\' in investing because it lowers your risk without necessarily lowering your return. It simply means not putting all your eggs in one basket. If you own only one airline stock and a pandemic hits, you lose everything; if you own the whole market, that loss is diluted by other winning sectors.\n\nThe goal is to own assets that are \'uncorrelated,\' meaning they don\'t all move in the same direction at the same time. When stocks are crashing, bonds or gold might be rising or staying stable. This balance smooths out the ride, preventing catastrophic losses in any single year.',NULL,NULL,15,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.954137',NULL),(1236,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/_GqAL7jD6vE',NULL,15,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.954742',NULL),(1237,3,'Key Concepts','text','Asset allocation is the practical way you implement diversification, deciding what percentage of your money goes where. A young investor might choose an 80/20 split (80% stocks, 20% bonds) for aggressive growth. A retiree might flip that to 20/80 to protect their wealth and generate income.\n\nUsing broad-market Index Funds or ETFs is the easiest way to achieve instant diversification. Buying a \'Total World Stock\' fund means you own a tiny slice of thousands of companies across the globe. This protects you from the failure of any single company or even any single country\'s economy.',NULL,NULL,15,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.955271',NULL),(1238,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 177}',15,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.955843',NULL),(1239,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Look at your current investments (or a mock portfolio). Metric: Count how many different companies or asset classes you hold. Question: If the tech sector crashed tomorrow, would your entire portfolio sink with it?',NULL,NULL,15,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:45.956380',NULL),(1240,1,'Overview','text','A goal without a plan is just a wish, and this is especially true for investing. Your investment plan starts with defining your \'Why\': are you saving for a house, freedom, or legacy? Your goal dictates your strategy; you wouldn\'t train for a sprint the same way you train for a marathon.\n\nOnce you have a target, you need to determine your contribution amount and frequency. Consistency is key; setting up an automatic monthly transfer takes the emotion out of the process. This habit, known as \'Dollar Cost Averaging,\' ensures you buy more shares when prices are low and fewer when they are high.',NULL,NULL,16,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.062182',NULL),(1241,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/qg_2QkO-Cfk',NULL,16,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.062920',NULL),(1242,3,'Key Concepts','text','Your plan should also include rules for \'rebalancing\' your portfolio periodically. If stocks have a great year, they might grow to take up too much of your portfolio, increasing your risk. Rebalancing involves selling some of the winners to buy more of the underperformers, bringing you back to your target allocation.\n\nFinally, the most difficult part of the plan is simply sticking to it when the market gets scary. History shows that investors who panic and sell during a crash almost always lose money compared to those who stay the course. Write your plan down when you are calm so you can refer to it when the market is chaotic.',NULL,NULL,16,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.063648',NULL),(1243,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 178}',16,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.064157',NULL),(1244,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down a simple 3-sentence investment policy statement (e.g., \"I invest £200 monthly into index funds for retirement.\"). Metric: The number of months you can commit to sticking to this without changing it. Question: What specific market event would tempt you to break your rules?',NULL,NULL,16,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.064708',NULL),(1245,1,'Overview','text','Real estate is one of the oldest and most reliable ways to build wealth, offering a tangible asset you can actually see and touch. Unlike stocks, which are often just digital figures on a screen, real estate provides practical utility as housing or commercial space while it grows in value. It is unique because it offers two simultaneous income streams: monthly cash flow from rent and long-term appreciation of the property price.\n\nMany investors flock to real estate because it serves as a powerful hedge against inflation over the long term. As the cost of living rises, property values and rental rates typically increase alongside them, effectively protecting your purchasing power. This characteristic makes it a foundational pillar for many diversified investment portfolios.',NULL,NULL,17,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.254242',NULL),(1246,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/U926I0fT6gY',NULL,17,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.254901',NULL),(1247,3,'Key Concepts','text','A key concept in real estate is \'leverage,\' which allows you to buy a large asset with a relatively small amount of your own money. By using a mortgage, you might pay only 20% of the property\'s price while the bank funds the other 80%, yet you keep 100% of the appreciation gains. This ability to control high-value assets with limited capital is a major accelerator for wealth building.\n\nHowever, real estate is also considered an \'illiquid\' asset, meaning you cannot quickly convert it into cash without significant time and effort. Selling a property can take months, involving inspections, negotiations, and legal paperwork, unlike selling a stock which takes seconds. Investors must be prepared to lock their money away for the long haul to see the best returns.',NULL,NULL,17,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.255412',NULL),(1248,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 179, \"expected_value\": 900}',17,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.256077',NULL),(1249,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Look up the average house price in your local area over the last 10 years to see the trend. Metric: Calculate the percentage increase in value from 10 years ago to today (Current Price - Old Price / Old Price). Question: Would you have made more money keeping cash in the bank or owning a property during that time?',NULL,NULL,17,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.256678',NULL),(1250,1,'Overview','text','Buying a property is a marathon, not a sprint, and the first step is getting your finances in order before you even look at a house. This means getting a \'pre-approval\' from a lender, which tells you exactly how much you can borrow and shows sellers you are a serious buyer. Without this, you risk falling in love with a property you simply cannot afford.\n\nOnce your budget is set, the search begins, often with the help of a real estate agent who knows the local market nuances. They can help you spot red flags, negotiate prices, and navigate the complex legal paperwork required to make an offer. A good agent pays for themselves by saving you from costly mistakes during the negotiation phase.',NULL,NULL,18,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.525430',NULL),(1251,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/5wNbF3O2s54',NULL,18,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.525852',NULL),(1252,3,'Key Concepts','text','After an offer is accepted, the \'due diligence\' period begins, where you must inspect the property rigorously. You should hire professional inspectors to check the roof, foundation, plumbing, and electrical systems for hidden damage. This is your last chance to back out or renegotiate if the house turns out to be a \'lemon\' with expensive problems.\n\nFinally, you reach \'closing,\' a meeting where mountains of documents are signed, and ownership is officially transferred. Be prepared for \'closing costs,\' which are extra fees for legal work, taxes, and loan setup that can add 2-5% to the final price. Once the money is wired and the deed is recorded, the keys are finally yours.',NULL,NULL,18,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.526307',NULL),(1253,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Dive into the real estate buying process, from assessing properties and securing financing to closing deals and handling paperwork.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 2: The Buying Process\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 180, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',18,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.526719',NULL),(1254,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Find a simple mortgage calculator online and input a realistic house price for your area. Metric: The estimated monthly payment including taxes and insurance versus your current rent. Question: Are you financially ready for the upfront closing costs, which could be thousands of dollars?',NULL,NULL,18,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.527129',NULL),(1255,1,'Overview','text','Rental property investing involves buying a property specifically to rent it out to tenants, generating monthly income. The goal is for the rent checks to cover the mortgage, insurance, taxes, and repairs, leaving you with profit every month. This surplus cash is known as \'positive cash flow,\' which is the lifeblood of a rental business.\n\nSuccess in this strategy relies heavily on choosing the right location where tenant demand is high and jobs are growing. You are not just buying a building; you are buying into the neighborhood\'s future economy and desirability. If you buy in a declining area, you may struggle to find quality tenants who pay on time.',NULL,NULL,19,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.627180',NULL),(1256,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/bMpFm9Oa5iA',NULL,19,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.627887',NULL),(1257,3,'Key Concepts','text','Being a landlord is an active job that involves managing both the physical asset and the human relationship with tenants. You must be prepared to handle late night calls about broken toilets or navigate strict laws regarding eviction and deposits. Many investors choose to hire a property manager to handle these headaches, though this eats into profits.\n\nYou must also account for \'vacancy rates,\' which is the time the property sits empty between tenants earning zero income. Smart investors always calculate their returns assuming the property will be empty for at least one month a year. Underestimating expenses like vacancy and repairs is the most common reason new investors lose money.',NULL,NULL,19,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.628490',NULL),(1258,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 181}',19,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.629184',NULL),(1259,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Search for a rental listing in your area and note the monthly rent asked. Metric: Compare that rent to the estimated mortgage payment you calculated in the previous lesson. Question: Does the rent cover the mortgage with enough room left over for repairs (the \'cash flow\')?',NULL,NULL,19,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.629820',NULL),(1260,1,'Overview','text','Determining the true value of a property is the most critical skill for an investor. You cannot rely on the asking price, which is just the seller\'s wish; you must determine the market value using \'Comps\' (Comparables). Comps are recently sold properties nearby that are similar in size, condition, and age.\n\nLook for at least 3-5 solid comparables sold in the last 6 months within a half-mile radius. If a 3-bedroom house next door sold for £200k, you shouldn\'t pay £250k for a similar one unless it has significant upgrades. This data-driven approach removes emotion from the buying process.',NULL,NULL,20,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.784887',NULL),(1261,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/3cXKsMAbXyI',NULL,20,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.785360',NULL),(1262,3,'Key Concepts','text','Another method is the \'Replacement Cost\' approach: asking how much it would cost to build this house from scratch today. If a house is selling for far less than the cost of the land plus construction materials, it might be a bargain. Conversely, paying double the replacement cost is usually a sign of a bubble.\n\nFor rental properties, use the \'Gross Rent Multiplier\' (GRM) or \'Cap Rate\' to value the income stream. A property might look cheap, but if the rent is low and expenses are high, it is worth less to an investor. Always verify the numbers yourself rather than trusting the agent\'s brochure.',NULL,NULL,20,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.785806',NULL),(1263,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 182, \"expected_value\": 900}',20,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.786292',NULL),(1264,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Pick a house for sale on Zillow/Rightmove and find 3 similar sold houses nearby. Metric: Calculate the average \'Price per Square Foot\' of the sold houses. Question: Is the house you are looking at priced above or below this average?',NULL,NULL,20,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.786689',NULL),(1265,1,'Overview','text','Real estate markets are not static; they move in four distinct phases: Recovery, Expansion, Hypersupply, and Recession. Understanding where your market sits in this cycle tells you whether to be aggressive or cautious. Buying at the peak of \'Hypersupply\' is dangerous, as prices often correct downward shortly after.\n\nIn the \'Expansion\' phase, rents and prices rise, and construction cranes are everywhere. This is when it is easiest to make money, but also easy to get overconfident. Smart investors watch for the \'Hypersupply\' phase, where unsold inventory starts to pile up, signaling a coming downturn.',NULL,NULL,21,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.896388',NULL),(1266,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/MIADgh6bUxo',NULL,21,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.896881',NULL),(1267,3,'Key Concepts','text','You must also track local trends like job growth and migration. A city where major companies are opening HQs will see rising property demand for years. Conversely, a one-industry town where the factory is closing is a value trap, no matter how cheap the houses look.\n\nDon\'t just look at national news; real estate is hyper-local. One neighborhood can be booming while another three miles away is declining. Drive the streets, talk to local shop owners, and look for signs of gentrification like new coffee shops or renovations.',NULL,NULL,21,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.897295',NULL),(1268,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Gain insight into the various market cycles (buyer???s market, seller???s market) and how to interpret trends to make informed investment choices.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 2: Real Estate Cycles and Trends\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 183, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',21,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.897817',NULL),(1269,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Search for \'population growth [Your City]\' and \'days on market [Your City]\'. Metric: If days on market are increasing, the market is cooling. Question: Are we currently in a buyer\'s market (easy to negotiate) or a seller\'s market (bidding wars)?',NULL,NULL,21,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:46.898270',NULL),(1270,1,'Overview','text','Risk management is about protecting your downside so the upside takes care of itself. The biggest risk for landlords is a bad tenant, which can lead to months of lost rent and legal fees. Rigorous tenant screening—checking credit, income, and references—is your first line of defense.\n\nAnother major risk is \'negative leverage,\' where the interest rate on your debt is higher than the return on the property. If your mortgage rate is 7% but the property only earns 5%, you are slowly going broke. Always ensure your deal has a healthy margin of safety to absorb interest rate hikes.',NULL,NULL,22,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.111086',NULL),(1271,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/n92RV9AQff0',NULL,22,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.111633',NULL),(1272,3,'Key Concepts','text','You must also carry proper insurance, not just for the building but for liability. If a tenant slips on an icy path and sues you, a standard homeowner\'s policy might not cover it. investing in an LLC structure can also protect your personal assets from lawsuits related to the property.\n\nFinally, maintain a cash reserve (liquidity) for the unexpected. Roofs leak and boilers break at the worst times. Running a real estate business with zero cash in the bank is like driving a car without a spare tire—eventually, you will get stranded.',NULL,NULL,22,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.112066',NULL),(1273,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 184}',22,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.112489',NULL),(1274,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Review your insurance policy or get a quote for \'Landlord Insurance.\' Metric: The deductible amount you would have to pay in an emergency. Question: Do you have at least 3 months of mortgage payments saved in a separate account?',NULL,NULL,22,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.112993',NULL),(1275,1,'Overview','text','The \'Fix and Flip\' strategy involves buying a distressed property, renovating it to increase its value, and selling it for a profit. It is a high-speed strategy that relies on finding a deal significantly below market value. The profit is made when you buy, not when you sell, so negotiating a low purchase price is critical.\n\nSpeed is the name of the game because every day you hold the property costs you money in loan interest, insurance, and taxes. Successful flippers have reliable contractor teams ready to start work the moment the deed is signed. It is less about investing and more about project management.',NULL,NULL,23,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.244384',NULL),(1276,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/S5n-PgG-AFE',NULL,23,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.244882',NULL),(1277,3,'Key Concepts','text','The biggest risk in flipping is underestimating renovation costs. A simple cosmetic update can turn into a nightmare if you find structural issues or mold behind the walls. Always add a contingency budget of at least 15-20% to your repair estimates to cover these surprises.\n\nYou must also understand the \'After Repair Value\' (ARV) perfectly before you buy. If you spend £50k fixing a house that only rises in value by £40k, you have lost money. You need to renovate to the standard of the neighborhood—don\'t put a gold tap in a budget home.',NULL,NULL,23,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.245343',NULL),(1278,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 185, \"expected_value\": 900}',23,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.245774',NULL),(1279,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Find a run-down property online and estimate the cost of a new kitchen and bathroom. Metric: Compare the total cost (Purchase + Repairs) to the price of renovated homes on the same street. Question: Is there enough margin left for a profit after paying selling fees?',NULL,NULL,23,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.246183',NULL),(1280,1,'Overview','text','Commercial real estate (CRE) includes offices, retail shops, industrial warehouses, and large apartment complexes. Unlike residential homes, which are valued based on emotion and comparable sales, CRE is valued strictly on the income it generates. If you can increase the rent roll or decrease expenses, you instantly force the value of the building up.\n\nCRE leases are generally longer (3–10 years) and often pass costs like taxes and maintenance on to the tenant (Triple Net Lease). This can make it a more passive investment than residential rentals. However, vacancies can last much longer; finding a new business tenant takes more time than finding a residential renter.',NULL,NULL,24,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.520018',NULL),(1281,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/oLxvasjA4Wc',NULL,24,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.520480',NULL),(1282,3,'Key Concepts','text','Financing commercial deals is different too; lenders care more about the building\'s profitability (Debt Service Coverage Ratio) than your personal income. They generally require larger down payments, often 30-40%, making the barrier to entry higher. This is a game for sophisticated investors with deeper pockets or partners.\n\nThe asset classes within CRE perform differently depending on the economy. For example, in a recession, luxury retail might suffer, but self-storage often thrives as people downsize. Diversifying across different types of commercial properties can protect your portfolio.',NULL,NULL,24,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.521002',NULL),(1283,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Understand how to evaluate and invest in commercial real estate, including office buildings, shopping centers, and multifamily units.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 2: Commercial Real Estate Investment\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 186, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',24,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.521436',NULL),(1284,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: identify one empty commercial unit in your local town center. Metric: Research the \'price per square foot\' for retail space in that area. Question: Why do you think that specific unit has remained empty?',NULL,NULL,24,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.521861',NULL),(1285,1,'Overview','text','A syndication is a fancy word for pooling money together with other investors to buy a large asset, like an apartment complex. It allows you to own a piece of a massive deal that you couldn\'t afford on your own. There are two roles: the General Partners (GPs) who do the work, and Limited Partners (LPs) who provide the money.\n\nAs a Limited Partner (passive investor), you get the benefits of real estate ownership—cash flow, appreciation, and tax breaks—without doing any work. You don\'t fix toilets or deal with tenants; you just read the quarterly reports and cash the checks. It is one of the truest forms of passive income.',NULL,NULL,25,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.695502',NULL),(1286,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/D8nU2C6FeCM',NULL,25,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.696073',NULL),(1287,3,'Key Concepts','text','The trade-off is that you have zero control over the day-to-day decisions. You are trusting the General Partner (Sponsor) to execute the business plan effectively. If they mismanage the property, your money is at risk, so vetting the operator is more important than vetting the property itself.\n\nMost syndications have a \'hold period\' of 3-7 years, meaning your money is locked up and illiquid during that time. You typically receive a \'preferred return\' (e.g., 7% annually) before the Sponsor gets paid, which aligns their interests with yours. It is a long-term play for wealth preservation and growth.',NULL,NULL,25,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.696773',NULL),(1288,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 187}',25,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.697380',NULL),(1289,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Search for \'Real Estate Syndication opportunities\' online and read a sample \'offering memorandum.\' Metric: Look for the \'minimum investment\' amount (usually $25k - $50k). Question: Are you comfortable locking your money away for 5 years without access to it?',NULL,NULL,25,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.697964',NULL),(1290,1,'Overview','text','Cryptocurrency is digital money that doesn\'t rely on a central bank or government to exist. Unlike the pounds or dollars in your bank account, which are controlled by institutions, crypto is decentralized and lives on a computer network. This means you have full ownership of your funds without needing permission from a middleman to spend or send them.\n\nIt is secured by cryptography—complex math puzzles—that make it nearly impossible to counterfeit. The most famous example is Bitcoin, but there are thousands of other \'coins\' designed for different purposes, from privacy to digital art. Understanding crypto is the first step to understanding the future of money.',NULL,NULL,26,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.874427',NULL),(1291,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/yg-rGHsWP-E',NULL,26,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.874929',NULL),(1292,3,'Key Concepts','text','The defining feature of cryptocurrency is \'peer-to-peer\' technology. If you want to send money to a friend in Japan, you send it directly from your digital wallet to theirs, bypassing expensive bank fees and slow processing times. The transaction is verified by the network, not by a bank employee, making it fast and global.\n\nHowever, this freedom comes with responsibility; because there is no bank, there is no customer support to call if you make a mistake. If you lose your password (private key) or send money to the wrong address, it is often gone forever. This \'be your own bank\' model is powerful but requires a higher level of personal security awareness.',NULL,NULL,26,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.875531',NULL),(1293,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Learn what cryptocurrency is, how it originated, and why it???s gaining popularity as a digital asset.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: What is Cryptocurrency?\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 188, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',26,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.876134',NULL),(1294,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Download a simple crypto wallet app (like Exodus or Trust Wallet) just to see the interface. Metric: Note how long it takes to set up compared to opening a traditional bank account. Question: How does it feel to be the only person with access to your account?',NULL,NULL,26,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:47.876634',NULL),(1295,1,'Overview','text','A blockchain is essentially a digital record book (ledger) that is shared across thousands of computers at once. Instead of one bank keeping the list of transactions, everyone on the network keeps a copy, making it incredibly difficult to cheat. When a page in the record book is full, it gets sealed and linked to the previous page, forming a \'chain\' of blocks.\n\nThis structure makes the data \'immutable,\' meaning once something is written to the blockchain, it cannot be deleted or changed. This transparency builds trust without needing a third party; you don\'t need to trust the person you are trading with, you only need to trust the code. It is the underlying technology that makes cryptocurrency possible.',NULL,NULL,27,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.096756',NULL),(1296,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/XaTqdCgbk7Y',NULL,27,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.097551',NULL),(1297,3,'Key Concepts','text','Transactions are verified through a process often called \'mining\' or \'staking,\' where computers solve puzzles to secure the network. In exchange for this work, the computers are rewarded with new coins, which is how new money enters the system. This clever incentive keeps the network running 24/7 without a CEO or manager.\n\nBecause the ledger is public, anyone can view the history of every transaction ever made. While your identity might be hidden behind a wallet address, the flow of money is completely visible. This radical transparency is a major shift from the secretive nature of traditional banking.',NULL,NULL,27,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.098297',NULL),(1298,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 189}',27,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.098911',NULL),(1299,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Visit a \'Blockchain Explorer\' website (like Etherscan or Blockchain.com) and look at the most recent transactions. Metric: The speed at which new blocks are being added (usually every 10 minutes for Bitcoin). Question: Why is an unchangeable record better for trust than a private database?',NULL,NULL,27,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.099663',NULL),(1300,1,'Overview','text','Not all cryptocurrencies are trying to be digital cash; they fall into different categories. \'Store of Value\' coins like Bitcoin are designed to be digital gold—scarce and secure, meant for long-term holding. \'Smart Contract\' platforms like Ethereum are more like digital oil, powering a network where developers can build apps and games.\n\nThen there are \'Stablecoins,\' which are pegged to real-world assets like the US Dollar to avoid volatility. These allow traders to keep money on the blockchain without worrying about the price crashing overnight. Understanding these differences helps you build a balanced portfolio rather than betting on random coins.',NULL,NULL,28,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.262199',NULL),(1301,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/P9myB85mK8g',NULL,28,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.262793',NULL),(1302,3,'Key Concepts','text','There is also a vast category of \'Altcoins\' (alternative coins) ranging from useful utility tokens to risky \'Meme coins.\' Utility tokens give you access to a specific service, like file storage or voting rights in a project. Meme coins, like Dogecoin, are driven purely by social media hype and community sentiment.\n\nBe cautious with newer, smaller coins, often called \'low-cap\' gems. While they offer the potential for massive returns, they also carry the highest risk of going to zero. A good rule of thumb is to keep the majority of your portfolio in established, \'blue-chip\' cryptocurrencies.',NULL,NULL,28,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.263218',NULL),(1303,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 190, \"expected_value\": 900}',28,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.263741',NULL),(1304,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: List the top 5 cryptocurrencies by market cap using a site like CoinGecko. Metric: Identify which category each one falls into (Store of Value, Smart Contract, or Stablecoin). Question: Which type of coin aligns best with your personal investment goals?',NULL,NULL,28,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.264268',NULL),(1305,1,'Overview','text','The easiest entry point for beginners is a Centralized Exchange (CEX) like Coinbase, Binance, or Kraken. These platforms act like a stock brokerage: you create an account, verify your identity (KYC), and link your bank account. They provide a user-friendly interface that makes buying crypto as simple as buying a book on Amazon.\n\nWhen buying, you can choose between a \'Market Order\' and a \'Limit Order.\' A Market Order buys immediately at the current best price, while a Limit Order lets you set a specific lower price you are willing to pay. Using limit orders helps you avoid overpaying during moments of high volatility.',NULL,NULL,29,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.390572',NULL),(1306,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/Yb6825iv0XM',NULL,29,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.391279',NULL),(1307,3,'Key Concepts','text','Before you deposit, be aware of the fees, which can range from 0.1% to over 3% depending on the payment method. Buying with a credit card is usually instant but carries the highest fees, while bank transfers take longer but are much cheaper. Always check the fee schedule to ensure you aren\'t losing a chunk of your investment to the middleman.\n\nAfter your purchase is complete, the crypto sits in a wallet controlled by the exchange. While this is convenient for trading, it means you don\'t technically own the coins—the exchange does. If the exchange pauses withdrawals or goes bankrupt, you could lose access to your funds, which is why long-term storage is best done elsewhere.',NULL,NULL,29,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.391934',NULL),(1308,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Explore the methods for purchasing cryptocurrency, including exchanges, wallets, and steps for setting up accounts.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: How to Buy Cryptocurrency\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 191, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',29,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.392477',NULL),(1309,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Create an account on a reputable exchange (you don\'t need to deposit money yet). Metric: Compare the fee for a debit card purchase vs a bank transfer on that platform. Question: Why is it risky to leave your entire life savings on an exchange?',NULL,NULL,29,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.392999',NULL),(1310,1,'Overview','text','Crypto storage is divided into \'Hot Wallets\' (connected to the internet) and \'Cold Wallets\' (offline). Hot wallets, like mobile apps or browser extensions, are convenient for daily spending but vulnerable to hackers. You should treat a hot wallet like the cash in your physical wallet: keep only what you need for short-term use.\n\nCold wallets, usually hardware devices like Ledger or Trezor, are the gold standard for security. They keep your private keys offline at all times, meaning a hacker would physically need to steal the device to get your funds. For any significant investment, a hardware wallet is not optional; it is essential insurance.',NULL,NULL,30,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.597149',NULL),(1311,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/Of_t7545tFs',NULL,30,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.598098',NULL),(1312,3,'Key Concepts','text','When you set up a wallet, you will generate a \'Seed Phrase\'—usually 12 or 24 random words. This phrase is the master key to your funds; if you lose your wallet device, this phrase restores your money on a new one. You must write this down on paper and hide it securely; never store it in a digital file or cloud storage where it can be hacked.\n\nNever share your seed phrase with anyone, ever. No support agent, website, or friend will ever legitimately ask for it. If someone asks for your seed phrase, they are 100% trying to steal your money. Your security is entirely in your own hands, so paranoia is a healthy habit in crypto.',NULL,NULL,30,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.599042',NULL),(1313,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 192}',30,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.600145',NULL),(1314,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: If you have a wallet, double-check that your seed phrase backup is physical (paper/metal) and not digital. Metric: The cost of a hardware wallet vs the value of your portfolio (is it worth the $60 investment?). Question: What is your plan if your house catches fire—is your backup safe?',NULL,NULL,30,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.601356',NULL),(1315,1,'Overview','text','Buying is easy, but selling is where the discipline is tested. Many investors watch their portfolio go up 500% and then ride it all the way back down because they didn\'t have an exit strategy. You should set clear price targets for taking profit before you even buy the coin, removing emotion from the heat of the moment.\n\nWhen you sell, you don\'t always have to cash out to your bank account. You can swap your volatile crypto for \'Stablecoins\' (like USDC) which hold a steady value. This keeps your capital ready on the exchange to buy the next dip without triggering the delays of moving money back and forth to a bank.',NULL,NULL,31,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.777601',NULL),(1316,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/lVSZ8Xt5sEs',NULL,31,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.778011',NULL),(1317,3,'Key Concepts','text','Be aware that trading one crypto for another is a taxable event in many countries. If you swap Bitcoin for Ethereum and have made a profit on the Bitcoin, you may owe Capital Gains Tax immediately. Keeping a detailed log of every trade is crucial so you don\'t get hit with a surprise bill from the tax man.\n\nDon\'t try to time the absolute top of the market; it is impossible. A better strategy is \'DCA Out\' (Dollar Cost Averaging), where you sell small chunks of your position as the price rises. This guarantees you lock in some profit while leaving some \'moon bags\' in case the price continues to go vertical.',NULL,NULL,31,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.778410',NULL),(1318,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 193, \"expected_value\": 900}',31,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.778846',NULL),(1319,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down a specific \'Take Profit\' price for one of your investments. Metric: Determine how much tax you would owe if you sold everything today. Question: Are you holding because you believe in the project, or because you are hoping to get rich quick?',NULL,NULL,31,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.779270',NULL),(1320,1,'Overview','text','Decentralized Finance, or DeFi, is a movement to rebuild the traditional banking system using blockchain technology. Instead of relying on banks to approve loans or hold deposits, DeFi uses \'smart contracts\'—automated code that runs on the blockchain. This allows anyone with an internet connection to access financial services without needing ID, a credit score, or permission.\n\nIn the DeFi world, you can lend your crypto to others to earn interest, borrow against your assets, or trade on decentralized exchanges. All of this happens peer-to-peer, meaning the fees that usually go to bankers now go to the users who provide liquidity. It represents a shift from centralized trust (in a bank) to decentralized trust (in code).',NULL,NULL,32,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.888535',NULL),(1321,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/k9HYC0EJU6E',NULL,32,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.889099',NULL),(1322,3,'Key Concepts','text','A popular DeFi activity is \'Yield Farming,\' where you move your crypto between different lending platforms to chase the highest interest rates. While the returns can be incredibly high compared to a savings account, the risks are also substantial. If the platform gets hacked or the coin value crashes, you can lose everything you deposited.\n\nOne of the biggest risks in DeFi is \'smart contract risk,\' where a bug in the code allows a hacker to drain the funds. Unlike a bank, there is no insurance policy or government bailout to restore your money. Users must be extremely careful and only use established, audited platforms (\"blue chips\") to minimize this danger.',NULL,NULL,32,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.889513',NULL),(1323,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Learn what DeFi is and how it aims to create a decentralized financial system without intermediaries.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: Decentralized Finance (DeFi)\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 194, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',32,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.889911',NULL),(1324,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Research the current \'TVL\' (Total Value Locked) of a major DeFi protocol like Aave or Compound. Metric: Compare the interest rate for supplying USDC (a stablecoin) on DeFi vs a traditional bank. Question: Is the extra interest worth the risk of technical failure?',NULL,NULL,32,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:48.890401',NULL),(1325,1,'Overview','text','Fungibility means that one item can be interchanged with another of the same type, like how one dollar bill is equal to any other dollar bill. A Non-Fungible Token (NFT) represents a unique digital asset that cannot be replicated or swapped one-for-one. This technology proves true ownership of digital items, from artwork and music to video game items and virtual land.\n\nBefore NFTs, it was impossible to prove you owned a digital image because anyone could just \'right-click and save\' it. An NFT acts as a digital certificate of authenticity stamped on the blockchain. Even if someone copies the image, they cannot copy the token that proves you are the original owner.',NULL,NULL,33,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.111718',NULL),(1326,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/Oz9zw7-_vhM',NULL,33,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.112319',NULL),(1327,3,'Key Concepts','text','NFTs have exploded in the art world, allowing artists to sell directly to collectors and even earn royalties every time their work is resold. This \'creator economy\' shift empowers artists who were previously cut out of secondary market profits. Beyond art, NFTs are being used for ticketing, exclusive community access, and digital identity verification.\n\nHowever, the NFT market is highly speculative and volatile, with prices driven almost entirely by hype and scarcity. Many projects turn out to be worthless after the initial buzz fades. Critics also point out the environmental impact of minting NFTs on energy-intensive blockchains, though the industry is moving toward greener solutions.',NULL,NULL,33,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.112935',NULL),(1328,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 195}',33,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.113496',NULL),(1329,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Visit an NFT marketplace like OpenSea and browse the top collections. Metric: Look at the \'Floor Price\' of a popular collection to see the minimum cost to buy in. Question: Do you see value in digital ownership, or does it feel like a bubble to you?',NULL,NULL,33,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.113965',NULL),(1330,1,'Overview','text','The future of crypto involves scaling solutions, often called \'Layer 2\' networks, which sit on top of main blockchains like Ethereum. These networks bundle thousands of transactions together to make them faster and cheaper, solving the problem of high fees. This infrastructure upgrade is essential for crypto to handle millions of daily users like Visa or Mastercard.\n\nAnother major trend is the rise of Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs), which are government-issued versions of crypto. While they use similar technology, they are centralized and controlled by the state, offering speed but zero privacy. This sets up a future clash between decentralized privacy coins and government surveillance currencies.',NULL,NULL,34,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.290911',NULL),(1331,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/0tZP8lR9kSk',NULL,34,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.291502',NULL),(1332,3,'Key Concepts','text','Institutional adoption is rapidly legitimizing the space, with major investment firms and pension funds adding crypto to their balance sheets. This influx of \'smart money\' reduces volatility over time but also correlates crypto more closely with the traditional stock market. We are moving from a \'Wild West\' era to a regulated financial asset class.\n\nFinally, the concept of \'Web3\' envisions a new internet owned by its users via tokens. Instead of Facebook or Google owning your data, you would own your content and social graph, taking it with you across different apps. This shift promises to redistribute the value of the internet back to the people who create it.',NULL,NULL,34,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.291966',NULL),(1333,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 196, \"expected_value\": 900}',34,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.292419',NULL),(1334,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Search for news on which countries are currently piloting a CBDC. Metric: The number of Fortune 500 companies that now hold Bitcoin on their balance sheets. Question: How would a government-controlled digital currency affect your financial privacy?',NULL,NULL,34,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.293039',NULL),(1335,1,'Overview','text','Forex, short for Foreign Exchange, is the global marketplace where national currencies are exchanged for one another. It is the largest and most liquid financial market in the world, with over $6 trillion traded every single day, dwarfing the stock market by a massive margin. Unlike the stock market, which has a central location like Wall Street, the Forex market is decentralized and operates electronically between banks, institutions, and individuals worldwide.\n\nThe market is open 24 hours a day, 5 days a week, because currencies are needed constantly for global trade and travel. When you go on holiday and swap your local currency for foreign cash, you are technically participating in the Forex market. However, traders participate not to buy souvenirs, but to speculate on the fluctuating values of these currencies to make a profit.',NULL,NULL,35,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.470219',NULL),(1336,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/f4Z8gJ-78dY',NULL,35,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.471052',NULL),(1337,3,'Key Concepts','text','In Forex, you are always buying one currency while simultaneously selling another, which is why they are quoted in pairs. The goal is to buy a currency that you believe will strengthen in value and sell a currency you believe will weaken. Because the market is so vast, no single entity can control the price for long, making it a highly dynamic environment driven by supply and demand.\n\nMajor players in this arena include central banks, massive commercial banks, and multinational corporations hedging against risk. Retail traders (individuals like you) make up a small but growing slice of the pie, thanks to online platforms that provide easy access. While the potential for profit is high due to market volatility, the risk of loss is equally significant if you do not understand the mechanics.',NULL,NULL,35,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.471570',NULL),(1338,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 197, \"expected_value\": 900}',35,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.472095',NULL),(1339,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check the current exchange rate between your local currency and the US Dollar (e.g., GBP/USD). Metric: Compare this rate to what it was exactly one year ago to see the percentage change. Question: What major global event do you think contributed most to that change in value?',NULL,NULL,35,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.472812',NULL),(1340,1,'Overview','text','Currencies in Forex are always traded in pairs, such as EUR/USD or GBP/JPY. The first currency listed is called the \'Base\' currency, and the second is the \'Quote\' currency. The price you see on the screen tells you how much of the Quote currency is required to buy one unit of the Base currency. For example, if EUR/USD is 1.10, it means 1 Euro costs 1.10 US Dollars.\n\nPairs are categorized into three main groups: Majors, Minors, and Exotics. \'Majors\' always include the US Dollar and are the most traded pairs in the world, offering the lowest costs (spreads) and highest stability. \'Minors\' (or Crosses) contain major currencies but not the US Dollar, while \'Exotics\' pair a major currency with one from a developing economy, like USD/TRY (Turkish Lira).',NULL,NULL,36,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.645319',NULL),(1341,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/p7gflr4-xGM',NULL,36,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.646149',NULL),(1342,3,'Key Concepts','text','When you trade a pair, you are essentially betting on the battle between two economies. If you \'buy\' (go long) EUR/USD, you are betting that the European economy will outperform the US economy, causing the Euro to rise in value. If the chart goes up, the Base currency is getting stronger; if it goes down, the Quote currency is winning.\n\nEvery pair has a \'Bid\' price (what you sell at) and an \'Ask\' price (what you buy at). The difference between these two prices is called the \'Spread,\' which is the fee the broker charges you to open the trade. Understanding how to read these pairs is the very first skill a trader must master before placing an order.',NULL,NULL,36,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.646620',NULL),(1343,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 198}',36,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.647058',NULL),(1344,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Open a Forex chart and identify the \'Major\' pair with the lowest spread. Metric: Calculate the cost of the trade (Spread) compared to the daily movement of the pair. Question: Why might a beginner want to avoid trading volatile \'Exotic\' pairs?',NULL,NULL,36,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.647504',NULL),(1345,1,'Overview','text','To survive in Forex, you must speak the language, starting with the \'Pip\' (Percentage in Point). A pip is the smallest standard unit of price movement, usually the fourth decimal place in a currency quote (0.0001). For most pairs, if the price moves from 1.1050 to 1.1051, that is a one-pip movement, which determines your profit or loss.\n\nTrade sizes are measured in \'Lots,\' with a \'Standard Lot\' being 100,000 units of currency. Because most people don\'t have $100,000 to trade, brokers offer \'Mini\' (10,000) and \'Micro\' (1,000) lots. Choosing the correct lot size is critical for risk management; trade too big, and a small move against you can wipe out your account.',NULL,NULL,37,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.805611',NULL),(1346,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/BiblWzD9T24',NULL,37,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.806133',NULL),(1347,3,'Key Concepts','text','\'Leverage\' is a tool that allows you to control a large position with a small amount of money. For example, with 1:100 leverage, you can control $100,000 worth of currency with just $1,000 of your own deposit. While this magnifies your potential wins, it also magnifies your losses, leading many beginners to lose their funds quickly.\n\n\'Margin\' is the actual money from your account that is set aside to keep a leveraged trade open. If your trade goes badly and your free margin drops too low, the broker will trigger a \'Margin Call\' and close your trades automatically. This safety mechanism protects the broker but locks in your losses permanently.',NULL,NULL,37,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.806543',NULL),(1348,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Familiarize yourself with essential forex terms, such as pips, lots, spreads, and leverage.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Key Forex Terminology\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 199, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',37,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.807022',NULL),(1349,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Use a \'Pip Value Calculator\' to find the value of 1 pip for a 0.10 lot size on GBP/USD. Metric: Multiply that pip value by 50 to see your potential profit (or loss) on a typical day trade. Question: Is that potential loss amount something you are comfortable with psychologically?',NULL,NULL,37,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.807438',NULL),(1350,1,'Overview','text','Technical Analysis is the study of historical price action to predict future price movements. Traders use charts to identify patterns and trends, operating on the belief that history tends to repeat itself. It focuses purely on the data on the screen—price and volume—ignoring the news or economic reports.\n\nThe foundation of technical analysis is understanding \'Support and Resistance.\' Support is a price level where buying interest is strong enough to overcome selling pressure (a floor), while Resistance is where selling interest overcomes buying pressure (a ceiling). Price often bounces between these levels, giving traders clear areas to enter and exit.',NULL,NULL,38,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.986110',NULL),(1351,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/EyTb0G0r6q0',NULL,38,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.986904',NULL),(1352,3,'Key Concepts','text','Traders also use \'Indicators\' like the Moving Average (MA) or Relative Strength Index (RSI) to help smooth out price noise. A Moving Average shows the average price over a set time, helping to visualize the overall trend direction. RSI helps identify when a currency is \'overbought\' (too expensive) or \'oversold\' (too cheap).\n\nHowever, it is important to remember that indicators are \'lagging,\' meaning they only tell you what has already happened. They should be used to confirm a trade idea, not as the sole reason to enter a trade. The most powerful indicator will always be the raw price action itself.',NULL,NULL,38,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.987511',NULL),(1353,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 200, \"expected_value\": 900}',38,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.988012',NULL),(1354,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Open a chart and draw horizontal lines at the most obvious \'peaks\' and \'valleys\' you see. Metric: Count how many times price touched your line and bounced back. Question: Do you see the price respecting these invisible levels?',NULL,NULL,38,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:49.988491',NULL),(1355,1,'Overview','text','While technical analysis looks at charts, Fundamental Analysis looks at the economic health of the countries behind the currencies. Factors like Interest Rates, GDP growth, and unemployment data drive the long-term trends of a currency pair. If a country\'s economy is strong, investors will buy its currency, driving the price up.\n\nThe most powerful driver in Forex is Interest Rates set by Central Banks (like the Federal Reserve). Generally, a higher interest rate yields a higher return on money invested in that currency, attracting global capital. Therefore, if a Central Bank raises rates, that currency typically strengthens against others.',NULL,NULL,39,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.103025',NULL),(1356,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/we_7w5z_bA4',NULL,39,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.103903',NULL),(1357,3,'Key Concepts','text','Traders watch the \'Economic Calendar\' religiously to know when major data releases like \'Non-Farm Payrolls\' (NFP) or inflation reports (CPI) are coming out. These events can cause massive volatility in seconds, often spiking price in both directions. Beginners are usually advised to stay out of the market during these high-impact news releases.\n\nFundamental analysis answers the question \'Why is the market moving?\', while technical analysis answers \'When should I enter?\'. Combining both gives you a complete picture. You might use fundamentals to decide *direction* (buy or sell) and technicals to decide *timing*.',NULL,NULL,39,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.104746',NULL),(1358,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 201}',39,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.105301',NULL),(1359,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Find an \'Economic Calendar\' online (e.g., ForexFactory) and look for a \'Red Folder\' (high impact) event this week. Metric: Watch the chart live when that news is released to see the volatility. Question: How many pips did the market move in the first minute of the news?',NULL,NULL,39,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.105789',NULL),(1360,1,'Overview','text','There are three main trading styles defined by how long you hold a trade: Scalping, Day Trading, and Swing Trading. Scalpers hold trades for seconds or minutes, aiming for tiny profits that add up over the day. It requires intense focus and fast reflexes but limits exposure to overnight risk.\n\nDay Traders open and close positions within the same day, never holding a trade overnight. They aim to capture the main move of the session. Swing Traders hold positions for days or weeks, aiming to capture larger market moves. This style requires less screen time but requires patience to sit through minor pullbacks.',NULL,NULL,40,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.289132',NULL),(1361,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/0w7gq7_0x0',NULL,40,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.289666',NULL),(1362,3,'Key Concepts','text','A popular strategy is \'Trend Following,\' where you identify the direction of the market (up or down) and simply trade with it. The saying \'The trend is your friend\' holds true; it is much easier to swim with the current than against it. Trend traders use pullbacks as opportunities to enter in the direction of the main trend.\n\nAnother strategy is \'Range Trading,\' used when the market is moving sideways between support and resistance. Traders buy at the support floor and sell at the resistance ceiling. Identifying whether the market is trending or ranging is the first step to choosing the right strategy for the day.',NULL,NULL,40,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.290106',NULL),(1363,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Learn some popular forex trading strategies, such as trend trading, range trading, and breakout strategies.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Commom Forex Strategies\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 202, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',40,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.290592',NULL),(1364,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Analyze your own personality and schedule. Metric: How much time per day can you dedicate to charts? Question: Are you patient enough for Swing Trading, or do you need the constant action of Scalping?',NULL,NULL,40,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.291074',NULL),(1365,1,'Overview','text','Leverage is often described as a double-edged sword because it magnifies both your profits and your losses equally. High leverage allows you to open large positions with a small deposit, which attracts many beginners looking to get rich quick. However, if the market moves just 1% against a highly leveraged position, it can wipe out your entire account instantly.\n\nPosition sizing is the mathematical formula used to determine how many lots to trade based on your risk tolerance. You should never determine your trade size by \'feel\' or by how much money you want to make. Instead, you calculate it based on where your Stop Loss is, ensuring you never risk more than 1-2% of your account on a single trade.',NULL,NULL,41,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.403384',NULL),(1366,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/BiblWzD9T24',NULL,41,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.404085',NULL),(1367,3,'Key Concepts','text','To calculate position size correctly, you must know your account balance, your risk percentage, and the distance to your Stop Loss in pips. If your Stop Loss is wide (far away), your position size must be smaller to keep the monetary risk the same. This dynamic adjustment ensures that a loss on a volatile pair costs you the exact same amount as a loss on a stable pair.\n\nIgnoring position sizing is the primary reason retail traders blow their accounts. They often trade the same lot size (e.g., 1.0 lot) on every trade regardless of the setup or stop loss distance. Professional traders obsess over risk management; amateurs obsess over potential profit.',NULL,NULL,41,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.404563',NULL),(1368,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 203, \"expected_value\": 900}',41,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.405124',NULL),(1369,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Use an online \'Position Size Calculator\' for a mock trade with a 20 pip stop loss and 1% risk. Metric: Note how the lot size changes if you increase the stop loss to 40 pips. Question: Why must you reduce your lot size when volatility increases?',NULL,NULL,41,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.405633',NULL),(1370,1,'Overview','text','A Stop Loss (SL) is an automatic order that closes your trade at a specific price to prevent further losses. It acts as your insurance policy; you hope you never need it, but you should never trade without it. Placing a hard stop loss at the moment you open a trade removes the temptation to hold onto a losing position in the hope that it turns around.\n\nA Take Profit (TP) is the opposite; it closes your trade automatically when the price reaches your target profit level. Greed often causes traders to hold winners too long until they reverse into losers, or fear causes them to close too early. A defined TP helps you lock in gains systematically according to your plan.',NULL,NULL,42,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.545168',NULL),(1371,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/9heC68T_rZ8',NULL,42,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.545797',NULL),(1372,3,'Key Concepts','text','The relationship between your Stop Loss and Take Profit is called the \'Risk-to-Reward Ratio\' (R:R). If you risk $50 to make $100, your ratio is 1:2, which is generally considered the minimum acceptable standard. With a 1:2 ratio, you can be wrong 60% of the time and still make money, because your wins are always double the size of your losses.\n\nAvoid placing your Stop Loss at arbitrary numbers like \'20 pips\' just because you feel like it. Stops should be placed at technical invalidation points, such as below a support level or above a resistance swing. If the price hits that level, your trade idea was wrong, and you should be out of the market immediately.',NULL,NULL,42,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.546242',NULL),(1373,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 204}',42,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.546727',NULL),(1374,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Look at a historical chart and identify a potential trade setup. Metric: Measure the distance to the logical Stop Loss and the logical Take Profit to find the R:R ratio. Question: Would you take a trade if the potential reward was smaller than the risk?',NULL,NULL,42,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.547190',NULL),(1375,1,'Overview','text','A trading plan is a comprehensive set of rules that defines exactly how, when, and why you will trade. It covers your strategy, your risk management parameters, and your daily routine. Without a written plan, you are not a trader; you are a gambler acting on impulse and emotion.\n\nThe plan acts as a contract with yourself to remove decision fatigue during the heat of battle. When the market is moving fast, you don\'t have time to think logically; you must rely on the pre-decided rules in your plan. If a trade setup doesn\'t meet every single criteria in your document, you simply do not take the trade.',NULL,NULL,43,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.696766',NULL),(1376,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/MvD7fQQ0szE',NULL,43,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.697389',NULL),(1377,3,'Key Concepts','text','Your plan should include a checklist for entry: What indicators must align? What timeframe are you trading? What is the maximum risk per trade? It should also define your \'state of mind\' rules, such as not trading when you are tired, angry, or distracted.\n\nReviewing and updating your plan is essential, but never change your rules in the middle of a trading session. Changes should only happen during the weekend when the market is closed and you are analyzing your journal data objectively. Sticking to a mediocre plan is often better than having no plan at all.',NULL,NULL,43,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.697953',NULL),(1378,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Discover how to create a personalized trading plan that includes risk management rules and trading goals.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Developing a Trading Plan\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 205, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',43,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.698580',NULL),(1379,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down 3 non-negotiable rules for your own trading plan (e.g., \"I will not trade during news events\"). Metric: The number of trades you took last week that actually followed your rules. Question: What is the consequence you will set for yourself if you break a rule?',NULL,NULL,43,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.699064',NULL),(1380,1,'Overview','text','Budgeting with an irregular income, like freelancing or commission-based work, requires a shift in strategy compared to a fixed salary. Instead of forecasting your average income, you should budget based on your lowest possible monthly income. This conservative approach ensures your essential bills are covered even during the lean months, preventing you from dipping into debt when work slows down.\n\nAny money earned above this \'base budget\' should be treated as a bonus, not spending money. This surplus should be immediately funneled into a specific \'Hill and Valley\' fund. This savings buffer acts as a reservoir you can draw from during low-income months to smooth out your cash flow and maintain a consistent lifestyle.',NULL,NULL,44,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.894902',NULL),(1381,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/y0i5A9A9Wjw',NULL,44,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.895412',NULL),(1382,3,'Key Concepts','text','The timing of your payments is just as important as the amount, as freelancers often face \'net-30\' or \'net-60\' payment terms. You must align your bill due dates with your most reliable cash flow periods or build a one-month buffer in your checking account. Living on last month\'s income—using money earned in January to pay February\'s bills—is the ultimate goal for breaking the feast-or-famine cycle.\n\nAdditionally, you must be disciplined about separating your business expenses from your personal finances. Mixing the two creates chaos during tax season and blinds you to your true take-home pay. By paying yourself a fixed \'salary\' from your business account to your personal account, you mimic the stability of a traditional job.',NULL,NULL,44,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.895883',NULL),(1383,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 206}',44,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.896314',NULL),(1384,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Calculate your lowest monthly income from the last 12 months. Metric: Compare this number to your \'survival budget\' (rent + food + utilities). Question: How large of a \'Hill and Valley\' fund do you need to survive 3 months of zero income?',NULL,NULL,44,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:50.896730',NULL),(1385,1,'Overview','text','A budget is a living document, not a stone tablet; it must evolve as your life changes. Major life events like moving house, getting a raise, or having a child fundamentally alter your financial landscape. If you try to stick to an outdated budget that doesn\'t reflect your current reality, you will inevitably fail and likely abandon the process entirely.\n\nEven without major events, inflation and changing habits mean you should review your budget numbers every few months. Perhaps your grocery bill has crept up due to price rises, or you canceled a gym membership you weren\'t using. Regular \'tune-ups\' ensure your plan remains accurate and effective, keeping you in control of your money.',NULL,NULL,45,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.111017',NULL),(1386,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/WMDUful-Hp4',NULL,45,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.111519',NULL),(1387,3,'Key Concepts','text','The \'Lifestyle Creep\' phenomenon is the biggest danger when adjusting your budget after a pay raise. It is natural to want to spend more when you earn more, but if your spending rises exactly in line with your income, you will never build wealth. A smart adjustment strategy is to allocate 50% of any new income to savings and only 50% to lifestyle upgrades.\n\nSchedule a \'State of the Budget\' meeting with yourself (and your partner) once a quarter. Look at your actual spending averages from the past three months rather than what you \'hoped\' to spend. Adjusting your targets to match reality is not a failure; it is a strategic recalibration.',NULL,NULL,45,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.111938',NULL),(1388,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 207, \"expected_value\": 900}',45,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.112393',NULL),(1389,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Compare your grocery budget to your actual grocery spending for the last 3 months. Metric: The difference (variance) between the plan and the reality. Question: Should you lower your spending or simply increase the budget to be more realistic?',NULL,NULL,45,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.112911',NULL),(1390,1,'Overview','text','In the modern era, you no longer need a physical ledger or even a spreadsheet to manage your finances effectively. Budgeting apps can connect directly to your bank accounts via \'Open Banking,\' automatically categorizing every transaction you make in real-time. This automation removes the friction of manual data entry, which is the number one reason people stop budgeting.\n\nTechnology also allows for \'envelopes\' or \'pots\' within digital bank accounts. You can separate your money into different buckets for rent, groceries, and savings the moment you get paid. This visual separation makes it impossible to accidentally spend your rent money on a night out, acting as a digital guardrail for your wallet.',NULL,NULL,46,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.296336',NULL),(1391,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/7sX3p00R_qA',NULL,46,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.296760',NULL),(1392,3,'Key Concepts','text','Beyond tracking, technology can automate your good habits through scheduled transfers and \'round-ups.\' Round-up features automatically round every purchase to the nearest pound and move the change into a savings account. It is a painless way to save hundreds a year without even noticing the money is gone.\n\nHowever, be careful not to rely so heavily on automation that you become disconnected from your spending. You still need to log in and check your app regularly to stay aware of your financial health. Technology is a tool to assist your decision-making, not a replacement for your awareness.',NULL,NULL,46,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.297216',NULL),(1393,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Explore the best budgeting apps and tools to simplify your financial planning.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Leveraging Technology for Budgeting\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 208, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',46,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.297622',NULL),(1394,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Enable \'transaction notifications\' on your banking app right now. Metric: The number of times you check your balance this week vs last week. Question: Does seeing an instant notification make you regret or reconsider a purchase?',NULL,NULL,46,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.298043',NULL),(1395,1,'Overview','text','The boundary between \'need\' and \'want\' has become blurred in a world of instant gratification. A \'need\' is essential for survival and basic functioning: shelter, basic food, utilities, and transport to work. A \'want\' is everything else—Netflix, dining out, brand-name clothes, and the latest iPhone.\n\nMarketing is designed to convince you that wants are needs (\'I *need* that coffee to function\'). Retraining your brain to label them correctly is the first step to conscious spending. You can still buy wants, but you should acknowledge them as luxuries you are choosing, not requirements you are forced to pay.',NULL,NULL,47,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.478650',NULL),(1396,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/bqlJvE21fd4',NULL,47,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.479225',NULL),(1397,3,'Key Concepts','text','Apply the \'50/30/20\' framework: 50% of income for Needs, 30% for Wants, and 20% for Savings. If your Needs exceed 50%, you are \'house poor\' or living beyond your means, leaving no room for fun or future growth. This structure gives you permission to spend 30% on fun without guilt because the essentials are covered.\n\nOften, we try to solve emotional needs with material wants. We buy clothes to feel confident or takeout to feel comforted. Recognizing the emotional drive behind a purchase helps you pause and ask: \'Is there a cheaper or healthier way to meet this need?\'',NULL,NULL,47,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.479781',NULL),(1398,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 209}',47,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.480356',NULL),(1399,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Label your last 5 transactions as \'Need\' or \'Want.\' Metric: The total dollar amount spent on wants this week. Question: Could one of those \'Needs\' (like a car payment) actually be a \'Want\' in disguise (a luxury car)?',NULL,NULL,47,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.480967',NULL),(1400,1,'Overview','text','Conscious spending is not about cutting everything; it is about spending extravagantly on the things you love and cutting costs mercilessly on the things you don\'t. Most people spend moderately on everything, ending up with a \'vanilla\' life they don\'t enjoy. Instead, pick your \'Money Dials\'—travel, food, or tech—and funnel your money there.\n\nThis approach removes the guilt associated with spending. If you value morning coffee, buy the best latte in town every day, but balance it by driving a used car or cooking dinner at home. It is about allocation, not deprivation. You are the CEO of your money, deciding which departments get the budget.',NULL,NULL,48,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.711377',NULL),(1401,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/zzYpMBjbPlc',NULL,48,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.711955',NULL),(1402,3,'Key Concepts','text','To make this work, you need a system. Automate your fixed costs and savings first so that whatever is left in your account is truly \'Guilt-Free Spending Money.\' When you know your bills and retirement are paid for, you can blow the rest on a nice dinner without checking your banking app under the table.\n\nReview your spending regularly to ensure it still aligns with your values. Sometimes we keep paying for a gym membership we idealized but never use. Conscious spending means being ruthless about cutting the dead weight so you can fund your dreams.',NULL,NULL,48,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.712478',NULL),(1403,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 210, \"expected_value\": 900}',48,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.713027',NULL),(1404,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one category you love (e.g., shoes) and one you don\'t care about (e.g., cable TV). Metric: The amount you can save by cutting the unloved category to zero. Question: How would it feel to spend that saved money on the thing you love instead?',NULL,NULL,48,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.713547',NULL),(1405,1,'Overview','text','Everything in life is negotiable, from your salary to your internet bill, yet most people accept the sticker price out of fear or politeness. Negotiating is not conflict; it is a business discussion to find a win-win solution. Companies expect you to negotiate and often have \'retention offers\' ready for anyone brave enough to ask.\n\nThe most powerful tool in negotiation is preparation. Know the market rate, know what competitors are offering, and be polite but firm. Calling your broadband provider and saying, \"I\'ve seen a better deal elsewhere, what can you do for me?\" can save you hundreds in five minutes. It is the highest hourly wage you will ever earn.',NULL,NULL,49,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.880530',NULL),(1406,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/6uVaXHoQpDU',NULL,49,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.881068',NULL),(1407,3,'Key Concepts','text','Be willing to walk away; it is your strongest leverage. If a seller knows you are desperate, they will never lower the price. By detaching yourself emotionally from the outcome, you gain the upper hand. Silence is also a tactic—make your request and then stop talking. The awkward silence often pressures the other person to fill the gap with a concession.\n\nStart small to build confidence: negotiate a discount on a damaged item or ask for a fee waiver at the bank. These low-stakes wins build the muscle memory needed for high-stakes negotiations like buying a car or asking for a raise. You don\'t get what you deserve; you get what you negotiate.',NULL,NULL,49,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.881478',NULL),(1408,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Master the art of negotiation to save money on big and small purchases.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Negotiating for Better Deals\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 211, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',49,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.881985',NULL),(1409,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Call one service provider (phone/internet) today and ask for a better rate or loyalty discount. Metric: The annual savings achieved from that one call. Question: What is the worst that can happen—they say no?',NULL,NULL,49,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:51.882440',NULL),(1410,1,'Overview','text','Most people leave their savings in a traditional bank account earning 0.01% interest, effectively donating their returns to the bank. A High-Yield Savings Account (HYSA) pays 10-20 times more interest for the exact same safety and liquidity. It is the easiest \'free money\' hack in personal finance, requiring zero effort once set up.\n\nHYSAs are usually offered by online banks that don\'t have the overhead costs of physical branches, allowing them to pass the savings on to you. They are FDIC (or FSCS) insured just like big banks, meaning your money is protected up to the government limit. There is literally no downside to switching your emergency fund to one of these accounts.',NULL,NULL,50,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.167646',NULL),(1411,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/ktHO0vChIhQ',NULL,50,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.168329',NULL),(1412,3,'Key Concepts','text','Compound interest works best when the rate is significant; earning 4% or 5% on your cash buffer makes a tangible difference over a year. For example, £10,000 in a traditional account earns £1 a year, but in a 5% HYSA, it earns £500. That covers a few bills or a nice dinner just for letting your money sit in the right place.\n\nBe mindful that interest rates are variable and will fluctuate with the central bank\'s base rate. However, they will always be superior to a standard checking account. Keep your \'spending money\' in checking and your \'saving money\' in a HYSA to separate your funds psychologically and mathematically.',NULL,NULL,50,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.169052',NULL),(1413,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"total\": 1000, \"question\": \"Allocate your £1000 across Needs, Wants, and Savings.\", \"categories\": [\"Needs\", \"Wants\", \"Savings/Debt\"], \"exercise_id\": 212}',50,'budget-allocation',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.170032',NULL),(1414,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Search \'Best High Yield Savings Rates\' right now and compare the top result to your current bank. Metric: Calculate the annual \'lost money\' by keeping your savings in a low-interest account. Question: Why have you not switched yet—is it laziness or loyalty?',NULL,NULL,50,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.170900',NULL),(1415,1,'Overview','text','Saving money can feel like a chore, but \'gamification\' hacks your brain\'s dopamine reward system to make it fun. By turning savings goals into levels, challenges, or quests, you shift your focus from restriction to achievement. This psychology is why video games are addictive, and you can apply the same logic to your bank account.\n\nTry visual trackers like a \'savings thermometer\' or a coloring chart on your fridge. Seeing your progress visually creates a sense of momentum that digital numbers on a screen often lack. Every time you color in a block, you get a micro-hit of satisfaction that reinforces the saving habit.',NULL,NULL,51,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.327958',NULL),(1416,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/mdGEKZwrmgc',NULL,51,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.328485',NULL),(1417,3,'Key Concepts','text','Popular challenges include the \'52-Week Challenge\' (save £1 week 1, £2 week 2...) or the \'100 Envelope Challenge.\' These structured games provide a clear roadmap and a definitive \'win\' condition. They break a massive, scary goal like \'save £5,000\' into tiny, manageable daily missions.\n\nYou can also use \'impulse save\' apps that punish or reward you based on your behavior. For example, some people set a rule: \'If I skip the gym, I must transfer £5 to savings.\' This links your financial health to your physical health, compounding your self-improvement efforts.',NULL,NULL,51,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.328915',NULL),(1418,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 213, \"expected_value\": 900}',51,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.329417',NULL),(1419,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Draw or print a simple progress bar for one specific savings goal (e.g., Holiday Fund). Metric: The percentage of the bar you can fill in today. Question: What small reward will you give yourself when you reach the 50% milestone?',NULL,NULL,51,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.329930',NULL),(1420,1,'Overview','text','You are likely bleeding money in small ways you don\'t even notice, often called the \'Latte Factor\' or \'Phantom Costs.\' Hidden savings aren\'t about cutting big things, but about optimizing the hundreds of tiny transactions. This includes unused subscriptions, bank fees, and food waste—money that leaves your pocket without bringing you any value.\n\nAudit your recurring bills; loyalty does not pay in the modern economy. Insurance and internet providers often offer \'new customer\' rates that are half what loyal customers pay. A quick 15-minute phone call to threaten cancellation can often unlock these hidden savings immediately.',NULL,NULL,52,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.488799',NULL),(1421,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/63KXihstu2Q',NULL,52,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.489393',NULL),(1422,3,'Key Concepts','text','Another massive hidden leak is convenience costs: delivery apps, pre-cut vegetables, or bottled water. You pay a premium of 30-100% just to save a few minutes of effort. Reclaiming these tasks—cooking a batch meal or carrying a water bottle—recovers hundreds of pounds a year with minimal lifestyle impact.\n\nFinally, check for \'zombie subscriptions\'—free trials you forgot to cancel or apps you haven\'t opened in months. Go through your last 3 months of bank statements line by line. Most people find at least £20-£50/month of pure waste that can be redirected to their freedom fund.',NULL,NULL,52,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.489880',NULL),(1423,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Find unexpected ways to cut costs and save more.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 3: Hidden Savings Opportunities\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 214, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',52,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.490303',NULL),(1424,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Scan your bank statement for recurring payments under £15. Metric: The annual cost of the subscriptions you don\'t use (Monthly x 12). Question: Would you rather have that service or the cash in your hand right now?',NULL,NULL,52,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.490750',NULL),(1425,1,'Overview','text','Passive income is money earned with minimal ongoing effort, effectively decoupling your time from your earnings. Unlike a salary, where you stop getting paid the moment you stop working, passive income continues to flow while you sleep. However, the term is misleading; it usually requires a massive amount of upfront work or capital to get the flywheel spinning.\n\nTrue passive income is rare; most \'side hustles\' are just second jobs in disguise. Real examples include dividends from stocks, interest from bonds, or rental income from property (if managed by others). The goal is to build enough of these streams to cover your living expenses, reaching the state known as financial independence.',NULL,NULL,53,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.700749',NULL),(1426,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/hVPGvWH0q_o',NULL,53,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.701402',NULL),(1427,3,'Key Concepts','text','For beginners, the most accessible passive stream is investing in low-cost Index Funds. By consistently buying the entire stock market, you let the world\'s companies work for you, paying you dividends and growing your capital over decades. This requires zero skill and minimal time, making it the ultimate \'lazy\' wealth builder.\n\nDigital products, like e-books or online courses, are another avenue, though they require significant upfront effort to create. Once built, they can be sold infinitely with zero replication cost, providing high-margin income. This scalability is the key difference between trading time for money and building a money-printing asset.',NULL,NULL,53,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.702031',NULL),(1428,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Learn how to create income sources that require minimal ongoing effort.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: Passive Income Streams\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 215, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',53,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.702694',NULL),(1429,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one asset you could buy or build this year that pays you without work. Metric: The potential monthly income from that asset (e.g., £5/month in dividends). Question: Are you willing to work for free upfront to build an asset that pays you forever?',NULL,NULL,53,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.703408',NULL),(1430,1,'Overview','text','Building wealth is offense, but protecting it is defense, and you need both to win the game. A single lawsuit, medical emergency, or scam can wipe out decades of saving if you are not properly shielded. Insurance—whether health, auto, or liability—is not a waste of money; it is the fee you pay to transfer catastrophic risk to someone else.\n\nDiversification is another layer of defense, ensuring that the failure of one asset class doesn\'t destroy your net worth. By spreading your money across stocks, bonds, cash, and real estate, you ensure that you can survive any economic season. Never putting all your eggs in one basket is the oldest and wisest rule in finance.',NULL,NULL,54,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.897814',NULL),(1431,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/5bDW06j6iTU',NULL,54,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.898333',NULL),(1432,3,'Key Concepts','text','Scams and fraud are increasingly sophisticated, targeting people who have finally built up some savings. Protect yourself by being skeptical of any \'opportunity\' that promises guaranteed high returns with zero risk. If it sounds too good to be true, it is almost certainly a trap designed to separate you from your money.\n\nFinally, estate planning is the ultimate form of protection for your family. Having a will and named beneficiaries on your accounts ensures your assets go exactly where you want them to without legal battles. It is an act of love to leave your financial house in order for those you leave behind.',NULL,NULL,54,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.898779',NULL),(1433,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 216}',54,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.899239',NULL),(1434,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check the beneficiaries listed on your primary bank and investment accounts. Metric: The date your will was last updated (or \'Never\'). Question: If you couldn\'t work for 6 months, does your current insurance cover your income?',NULL,NULL,54,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:52.899762',NULL),(1435,1,'Overview','text','Inflation is the silent killer of wealth, slowly eroding the purchasing power of your money over time. If inflation is 3% per year, your £100 today will only buy £97 worth of goods next year. This means that keeping your long-term savings in a checking account is effectively losing money every single day.\n\nThis \'money decay\' explains why you must invest rather than just save. To build wealth, your money must grow at a rate higher than inflation; otherwise, you are running on a treadmill just to stay in place. Investing in assets like stocks or real estate acts as a shield, as their value typically rises along with consumer prices.',NULL,NULL,55,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.065802',NULL),(1436,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/LCVMVs797h4',NULL,55,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.066324',NULL),(1437,3,'Key Concepts','text','However, inflation can actually benefit those with fixed-rate debt, like a mortgage. As the value of money drops, the \'real\' value of your debt decreases—you are paying back the loan with cheaper dollars in the future. This is why borrowing to buy appreciating assets is a popular strategy during high-inflation periods.\n\nUnderstanding the Consumer Price Index (CPI) helps you gauge the real cost of living versus your income growth. If your salary raise is 2% but inflation is 5%, you have effectively taken a 3% pay cut. You must advocate for inflation-adjusted wages to maintain your standard of living.',NULL,NULL,55,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.066789',NULL),(1438,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 217, \"expected_value\": 900}',55,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.067244',NULL),(1439,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Find the current inflation rate for your country online. Metric: Compare it to the interest rate on your savings account (Inflation - Interest = Real Return). Question: Is your \'safe\' money actually safe, or is it slowly evaporating?',NULL,NULL,55,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.067664',NULL),(1440,1,'Overview','text','Your \'money story\' is the subconscious narrative running in the background of your mind, shaped heavily by your childhood experiences. If you grew up hearing phrases like \'money doesn\'t grow on trees\' or saw your parents arguing about bills, you likely associate money with scarcity and conflict. Recognizing these hidden scripts is the first step to rewriting them, as they often dictate your adult financial behavior without you even realizing it.\n\nMany of us carry \'financial trauma\' that manifests as either avoidance (ignoring bank statements) or hyper-vigilance (saving every penny out of fear). By bringing these memories into the light, you can separate the past from the present and choose new beliefs that serve your goals. You are not destined to repeat your parents\' financial mistakes.',NULL,NULL,56,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.268048',NULL),(1441,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/K6ACdXZAuco',NULL,56,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.268716',NULL),(1442,3,'Key Concepts','text','To uncover your story, ask yourself what your earliest memory of money is and how it made you feel. Was it a feeling of shame when you couldn\'t afford a school trip, or pride when you saved for a toy? These emotional imprints create neural pathways that trigger automatic reactions to financial stress today.\n\nOnce identified, you can challenge these scripts with evidence from your current life. For example, if your script is \'I\'m bad with numbers,\' replace it with \'I am learning to manage my money competently.\' This cognitive reframing turns a fixed mindset into a growth mindset, opening the door to financial confidence.',NULL,NULL,56,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.269295',NULL),(1443,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Explore how your past experiences shape your financial behaviors today.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: Understanding Your Money Story\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 218, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',56,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.270064',NULL),(1444,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down the most common phrase about money you heard growing up. Metric: Rate on a scale of 1-10 how true that phrase feels to you today. Question: Is this belief actually yours, or did you just inherit it?',NULL,NULL,56,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.270747',NULL),(1445,1,'Overview','text','Money blocks are psychological barriers that prevent you from achieving wealth, often rooted in a fear of success or a feeling of unworthiness. Common blocks include the belief that \'rich people are greedy\' or that \'I don\'t deserve to have more than I need.\' These thoughts act like a glass ceiling, causing you to self-sabotage whenever you get close to a financial breakthrough.\n\nSelf-sabotage can look like overspending immediately after getting a bonus or procrastinating on investing despite knowing you should start. It is your subconscious mind trying to keep you in your \'safe zone,\' even if that zone is broke. Breaking through requires proving to your brain that it is safe to have money.',NULL,NULL,57,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.403141',NULL),(1446,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/vypmKCyVxrE',NULL,57,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.403894',NULL),(1447,3,'Key Concepts','text','One powerful technique to dissolve blocks is the \'Adding Zero\' exercise, where you visualize your bank account with an extra zero at the end. Notice the physical sensations that arise—is it excitement, or is it anxiety and guilt? Sitting with that discomfort and breathing through it helps expand your nervous system\'s capacity to hold more wealth.\n\nAnother strategy is to surround yourself with people who normalize wealth rather than demonize it. If your peer group constantly complains about being broke, your mirror neurons will mimic that reality to fit in. Curating your environment to include financially positive influences helps rewire your brain for abundance.',NULL,NULL,57,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.404672',NULL),(1448,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 219}',57,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.405388',NULL),(1449,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one specific way you have self-sabotaged financially in the past (e.g., spending tax money). Metric: The emotional trigger that preceded that action (stress, boredom, fear). Question: What simple safety mechanism can you put in place to stop this happening again?',NULL,NULL,57,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.405946',NULL),(1450,1,'Overview','text','Gratitude is not just a feel-good emotion; it is a practical \'wealth switch\' that shifts your focus from lack to abundance. When you obsess over what you don\'t have, you train your brain to spot scarcity, missing the opportunities right in front of you. Practicing gratitude rewires your reticular activating system (RAS) to spot resources, connections, and money that were there all along.\n\nThis shift in vibration changes how you show up in the world, making you more magnetic to opportunities. People prefer to do business with those who are appreciative and optimistic rather than those who are desperate and complaining. Gratitude signals to your subconscious that you already have enough, which paradoxically opens the floodgates for more.',NULL,NULL,58,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.544100',NULL),(1451,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/QELLk-T3dsg',NULL,58,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.544605',NULL),(1452,3,'Key Concepts','text','To make gratitude effective, you must feel it emotionally, not just list items robotically. Spending two minutes a day deeply feeling the security your current income provides—however small—creates a foundation of safety. This \'emotionalized\' gratitude dissolves the fear that drives bad financial decisions like panic selling or retail therapy.\n\nAdvanced gratitude involves being thankful for money *before* you even receive it. This practice, often used by high achievers, aligns your identity with the future you are creating. It acts as a rehearsal for success, reducing the impostor syndrome that often strikes when you finally hit your goals.',NULL,NULL,58,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.545150',NULL),(1453,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 220, \"expected_value\": 900}',58,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.545668',NULL),(1454,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Start a \'Money Gratitude Journal\' and write down 3 things your money bought you today (even just a coffee). Metric: The shift in your mood before and after writing. Question: Can you find one thing to be grateful for about a bill you have to pay (e.g., electricity gives me light)?',NULL,NULL,58,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.546300',NULL),(1455,1,'Overview','text','The famous \'Marshmallow Test\' showed that children who could wait for a second marshmallow ended up more successful in life than those who ate the first one immediately. This ability to delay gratification is the master key to financial wealth. Every time you invest, you are choosing to not eat the marshmallow today so you can have two (or ten) in the future.\n\nWe live in an instant-gratification society that profits from your impatience. One-click ordering and \'Buy Now, Pay Later\' schemes are designed to bypass your logical brain and exploit your impulse for immediate reward. resisting this pressure requires conscious effort and a strong connection to your future goals.',NULL,NULL,59,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.709069',NULL),(1456,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/M0yhHKWBppg',NULL,59,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.709543',NULL),(1457,3,'Key Concepts','text','Implement the \'72-Hour Rule\' to strengthen this muscle. When you see something you want to buy (that isn\'t a necessity), force yourself to wait 72 hours. Usually, the dopamine rush fades, and you realize you don\'t actually need the item. This simple pause saves thousands of pounds a year in impulse purchases.\n\nThink of your future self as a real person you love and want to take care of. When you spend all your money today, you are stealing from that future person. Delayed gratification is ultimately an act of self-love, ensuring that \'Future You\' is safe, wealthy, and free.',NULL,NULL,59,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.709972',NULL),(1458,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Learn why waiting to make purchases can benefit your financial future.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: The Power of Delayed Gratification\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 221, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',59,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.710494',NULL),(1459,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one item you were planning to buy this week. Metric: Calculate what that money would grow to in 10 years if invested at 7% instead. Question: Is the item worth more to you than that future amount of cash?',NULL,NULL,59,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.711209',NULL),(1460,1,'Overview','text','Financial boundaries are the rules you set to protect your money from the demands of others and social pressure. It is often harder to say \'no\' to a friend\'s dinner invitation or a family member asking for a loan than it is to budget alone. However, without these boundaries, your financial plan is at the mercy of everyone else\'s whims.\n\nLearn the power of the phrase: \"That\'s not in my budget right now.\" It is a polite but firm way to decline expensive outings without making it about not liking the person. True friends will respect your goals; those who pressure you to spend money you don\'t have are prioritizing their fun over your financial security.',NULL,NULL,60,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.900234',NULL),(1461,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/V1Z_9vP4r30',NULL,60,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.900750',NULL),(1462,3,'Key Concepts','text','Be wary of \'FOMO\' (Fear Of Missing Out), which is a major driver of boundary violations. Social media presents a curated highlight reel of other people\'s spending, making you feel like you are falling behind. Remember that you are seeing their spending, not their debt; many people living lavishly online are secretly broke.\n\nSetting boundaries also applies to yourself. You might set a rule like \"I never put clothes on a credit card\" or \"I only eat out on weekends.\" These personal laws reduce decision fatigue because the answer is already decided before the temptation arises.',NULL,NULL,60,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.901237',NULL),(1463,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 222}',60,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.901754',NULL),(1464,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Practice saying \"I\'m saving for a big goal, so I\'ll pass this time\" in the mirror. Metric: The amount of money saved by declining one social event this month. Question: Which specific friend or family member is the hardest for you to say \'no\' to?',NULL,NULL,60,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:53.902203',NULL),(1465,1,'Overview','text','Motivation is fleeting, but habits are reliable. You don\'t rise to the level of your goals; you fall to the level of your systems. Building wealth is rarely about one big lucky break; it is the result of boring, small, repetitive actions taken consistently over a long period of time.\n\nStart with \'Atomic Habits\'—tiny changes that are too small to fail. Instead of trying to save 50% of your income overnight, start by saving 1%. Instead of overhauling your entire portfolio, start by tracking your spending for one minute a day. Success feeds on itself; once you master the small habit, you can scale it up.',NULL,NULL,61,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.019101',NULL),(1466,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/PZ7lDrwYdZc',NULL,61,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.019873',NULL),(1467,3,'Key Concepts','text','Automation is the ultimate habit hack because it removes human error and willpower from the equation. If your savings and investments leave your account automatically on payday, you are disciplined by default. You adapt your lifestyle to what is left over, ensuring you always pay your future self first.\n\nFocus on identity-based habits. Instead of saying \"I\'m trying to save,\" say \"I am a saver.\" When you shift your identity, your actions naturally align with it because humans have a deep drive to be consistent with how they view themselves. Prove this new identity to yourself with small wins every day.',NULL,NULL,61,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.020466',NULL),(1468,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 223, \"expected_value\": 900}',61,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.021215',NULL),(1469,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Set up one automated transfer (even £5) to a savings account this week. Metric: The number of days in a row you can track your spending (your \'streak\'). Question: What is one \'bad\' money habit you have, and what is the \'cue\' that triggers it?',NULL,NULL,61,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.021645',NULL),(1470,1,'Overview','text','Failure is not the opposite of success; it is a necessary stepping stone on the path to success. Everyone who has built significant wealth has made mistakes, lost money, or bought a bad investment at some point. The difference between those who stay broke and those who recover is the ability to reframe failure as feedback rather than a character flaw.\n\nShame is the biggest enemy of resilience; it convinces you to hide your mistakes rather than fix them. If you carry debt or made a bad trade, acknowledge it, forgive yourself, and focus on the data. Ask \'What went wrong in my process?\' rather than \'What is wrong with me?\' to turn the pain into a lesson.',NULL,NULL,62,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.121990',NULL),(1471,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/zLb3u5hX1Q0',NULL,62,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.122635',NULL),(1472,3,'Key Concepts','text','Adopt a \'scientist mindset\' towards your finances: a failed experiment is just data that tells you what doesn\'t work. This detachment allows you to analyze your budget or portfolio objectively without getting emotional. When you remove the emotion from the error, you can implement a logical fix immediately, preventing the hole from getting deeper.\n\nRemember that your net worth is not your self-worth. You are a human being having a financial experience, and money is simply a tool you are learning to master. By sharing your stories of failure with trusted friends, you often realize you are not alone, which dissolves the shame and empowers you to move forward.',NULL,NULL,62,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.123307',NULL),(1473,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Turn setbacks into learning opportunities for future success.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: Reframing Financial Failures\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 224, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',62,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.123984',NULL),(1474,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one financial mistake you are still beating yourself up about. Metric: Write down one specific lesson you learned from that mistake that will save you money in the future. Question: Can you forgive yourself today so you can start fixing it tomorrow?',NULL,NULL,62,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.124597',NULL),(1475,1,'Overview','text','Financial resilience begins with the understanding that unexpected expenses are not \'if\' but \'when.\' Cars break down, boilers burst, and jobs can be lost; these are normal parts of life, not bad luck. An \'Emergency Mindset\' means you stay prepared for these events so they remain minor inconveniences rather than becoming life-altering disasters.\n\nThe cornerstone of this preparation is the Emergency Fund—a stash of cash that is easily accessible and strictly for crises. Knowing this money is there changes your psychology, lowering your baseline stress levels significantly. You walk taller knowing that you can handle a surprise bill without needing to beg a bank for a loan.',NULL,NULL,63,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.270325',NULL),(1476,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/q3aQbW2d2-8',NULL,63,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.271213',NULL),(1477,3,'Key Concepts','text','Start by aiming for a \'Starter Emergency Fund\' of £1,000 or one month of expenses. This small barrier protects you from the most common issues like car repairs or dental work. Once you are out of high-interest debt, expand this to a fully-funded safety net covering 3 to 6 months of living expenses.\n\nKeep this money separate from your checking account so you don\'t accidentally spend it on pizza or clothes. It needs to be liquid (cash), not invested in stocks or locked in property, because emergencies don\'t wait for the market to open. Think of it as self-insurance; the \'return\' on this money is not interest, but peace of mind.',NULL,NULL,63,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.271855',NULL),(1478,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 225}',63,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.272465',NULL),(1479,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check your current savings balance. Metric: Calculate how many months you could survive if your income went to zero today. Question: Is that number high enough to let you sleep soundly at night?',NULL,NULL,63,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.273041',NULL),(1480,1,'Overview','text','Financial stress triggers the body\'s \'fight or flight\' response, which literally shuts down the part of your brain responsible for logical long-term planning. When you are panicked about money, you are biologically wired to make bad, short-sighted decisions. Recognizing this physical reaction is the first step to pausing and regaining control before you act.\n\nThe antidote to anxiety is action, but it must be small, manageable action. Instead of trying to solve your entire debt problem in one day, focus on one tiny step, like organizing your bills or calling one creditor. Action clears the fog of fear and proves to your brain that the monster is smaller than it looks in the dark.',NULL,NULL,64,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.386287',NULL),(1481,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/3x-lW5KqXk0',NULL,64,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.386937',NULL),(1482,3,'Key Concepts','text','Focus on what you can control—your spending and your habits—rather than what you can\'t, like the economy or inflation. Obsessing over global news headlines only drains your energy without fixing your bank account. Create a \'Circle of Control\' list: ignore the noise outside and execute ruthlessly on the items inside.\n\nSelf-care is often seen as a luxury, but during financial stress, it is a necessity. Simple, free things like getting enough sleep, walking outside, and drinking water help regulate your nervous system. You cannot make smart, complex financial decisions if you are exhausted and burned out.',NULL,NULL,64,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.387571',NULL),(1483,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 226, \"expected_value\": 900}',64,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.388041',NULL),(1484,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down 3 things causing you financial stress right now. Metric: Circle the ones you can actually control or influence today. Question: What is one free activity you can do this evening to lower your cortisol levels?',NULL,NULL,64,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.388541',NULL),(1485,1,'Overview','text','In a rapidly changing economy, the skills that got you your current job might not be enough to keep it in ten years. Financial growth is directly linked to your ability to adapt and learn new high-value skills. The most successful investors and entrepreneurs see education not as a phase of life that ends at graduation, but as a lifelong daily habit.\n\nYour \'Human Capital\'—your ability to earn money—is the most valuable asset you will ever own, far exceeding any stock portfolio. investing in yourself through courses, books, or coaching often yields the highest Return on Investment (ROI) of any expenditure. When you increase your skill set, you increase your marketplace value, which directly correlates to higher income potential.',NULL,NULL,65,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.612807',NULL),(1486,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/7R_u4Xl2pKE',NULL,65,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.613413',NULL),(1487,3,'Key Concepts','text','Curiosity is the engine of wealth; it drives you to ask how systems work, where opportunities lie, and how to solve expensive problems. Instead of zoning out on social media, use your free time to study trends in your industry or learn the basics of a new technology like AI. Even reading just 10 pages of a non-fiction book a day amounts to 12-15 books a year, putting you ahead of 90% of your peers.\n\nLearning doesn\'t always have to be formal or expensive; podcasts and free online tutorials are powerful tools if used consistently. The key is application—learning something and immediately testing it in the real world. Knowledge without action is merely entertainment; applied knowledge is power.',NULL,NULL,65,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.613869',NULL),(1488,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Pick the best answer based on the overview and video.\", \"options\": [\"Apply: Discover the value of continuous education in achieving financial growth.\", \"Memorize definitions without context\", \"Ignore practical application\", \"Skip straight to the next lesson\"], \"question\": \"Which option best reflects the main goal of \'Lesson 1: Embracing Lifelong Learning\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 227, \"explanation\": \"Aim to apply the concept to your real context.\", \"correctAnswer\": 0}',65,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.614310',NULL),(1489,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one skill that is currently in high demand in your industry (e.g., data analysis, public speaking). Metric: The cost (time or money) to learn the basics of that skill this month. Question: How much could your income increase if you mastered this new capability?',NULL,NULL,65,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.614741',NULL),(1490,1,'Overview','text','The saying \'your network is your net worth\' is a cliché because it is fundamentally true. Most high-paying jobs and investment opportunities are never advertised publicly; they fill through personal referrals and connections. Building a strong network acts as a multiplier for your hard work, opening doors that would otherwise remain locked.\n\nHowever, true networking is not about handing out business cards or asking for favors; it is about adding value to others. The best networkers approach people with the mindset of \'How can I help you?\' rather than \'What can you do for me?\' By being generous with your time and expertise first, you build a reservoir of goodwill that eventually comes back to you.',NULL,NULL,66,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.794459',NULL),(1491,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/jC_U6F6lR3o',NULL,66,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.794997',NULL),(1492,3,'Key Concepts','text','Audit the five people you spend the most time with, as they act as a mirror for your own financial future. If your inner circle has poor financial habits and no ambition, it is incredibly difficult for you to rise above that standard. You don\'t need to ditch your old friends, but you must actively seek out mentors and peers who are playing the game at a higher level than you.\n\nNetworking has also been democratized by the internet; you can connect with industry leaders via LinkedIn or Twitter (X) instantly. Sending a thoughtful, specific message about their work can spark a relationship with someone thousands of miles away. Consistency in showing up and engaging with your community is the secret to staying top-of-mind.',NULL,NULL,66,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.795420',NULL),(1493,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"Budget\", \"color\": \"#F1F5F9\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Income\", \"color\": \"#EEF2FF\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Expense\", \"color\": \"#ECFEFF\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"budget\", \"text\": \"A plan for your money\"}, {\"id\": \"income\", \"text\": \"Money coming in\"}, {\"id\": \"expense\", \"text\": \"Money going out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 228}',66,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.795881',NULL),(1494,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Reach out to one person in your field who you admire and send them a genuine compliment or question. Metric: The number of new professional connections you make this month. Question: Who in your current circle inspires you to be better with money?',NULL,NULL,66,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.796302',NULL),(1495,1,'Overview','text','Most people overestimate what they can do in a day but underestimate what they can do in a decade. A financial vision is a high-definition picture of your future life that acts as a compass for your daily decisions. Without a clear destination, you will wander aimlessly, reacting to immediate expenses rather than building toward a specific outcome.\n\nSet \'Big Hairy Audacious Goals\' (BHAGs) that scare you slightly; if your goal is too easy, it won\'t demand enough growth from you to achieve it. Instead of saying \'I want to be rich,\' say \'I want a £2 million net worth and a villa in Spain by age 50.\' Specificity triggers your brain to start finding the solutions and resources needed to make it happen.',NULL,NULL,67,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.911332',NULL),(1496,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch the video and note 2–3 concrete takeaways. Pause where needed.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/t1kHk336DYY',NULL,67,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.911829',NULL),(1497,3,'Key Concepts','text','Once the big vision is set, you must reverse-engineer it into actionable yearly, monthly, and weekly steps. If you need £1 million in 20 years, mathematics will tell you exactly how much you need to invest starting today. This breaks a mountainous goal down into a manageable slope, reducing overwhelm and preventing procrastination.\n\nReview your goals frequently—at least once a quarter—to ensure they still align with your values. It is okay to change your mind and adjust your course as you grow and learn. The purpose of the goal is not just the achievement, but the person you must become in the process of chasing it.',NULL,NULL,67,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.912413',NULL),(1498,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"Enter the exact amount.\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 229, \"expected_value\": 900}',67,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.913128',NULL),(1499,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write a paragraph describing your ideal financial life exactly 10 years from today. Metric: Break that vision down into one specific financial target for this year. Question: Does your current spending and saving behavior align with that 10-year vision?',NULL,NULL,67,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 20:57:54.913838',NULL),(1503,1,'Overview','text','Real estate is unique among asset classes because it allows you to use \'leverage\' safely, meaning you can buy a large asset with a small percentage of your own money. Typically, you put down a deposit of 20-25%, and the bank lends you the rest via a mortgage. This amplifies your returns; if the property value goes up by 5%, your actual return on cash invested could be 20% or more because you keep all the profit.\n\nHowever, leverage is a double-edged sword that increases risk as well as reward. If property values drop, you still owe the full amount of the loan to the bank, potentially leaving you in \'negative equity\' where the house is worth less than the mortgage. Understanding the terms of your loan—interest rates, fixed periods, and repayment penalties—is just as important as finding the right house.',NULL,NULL,69,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.383254',NULL),(1504,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/InGK2tKQb1k',NULL,69,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.386562',NULL),(1505,3,'Key Concepts','text','The \'Loan-to-Value\' (LTV) ratio is the key metric lenders use to decide how risky you are. A 75% LTV means you are borrowing 75% of the property\'s price and putting down 25% cash. generally, the lower the LTV, the better interest rate you will receive because the bank has a larger safety cushion if they have to foreclose.\n\nInvestors must also choose between \'Interest-Only\' and \'Repayment\' mortgages. An Interest-Only loan keeps monthly payments low, improving cash flow, but you never actually pay off the debt unless you sell the house. A Repayment mortgage costs more monthly but slowly builds your ownership (equity) in the property over time.',NULL,NULL,69,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.388911',NULL),(1506,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"You buy a £200,000 house with a 25% deposit. How much cash (the deposit) do you need upfront?\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 230, \"expected_value\": 50000}',69,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.397473',NULL),(1507,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check current mortgage rates for a \'Buy-to-Let\' or investment property in your region. Metric: Calculate the difference in monthly payments between a 25% deposit and a 40% deposit. Question: Is it better to put more money down to lower the monthly cost, or keep that cash for a second investment?',NULL,NULL,69,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.391897',NULL),(1508,1,'Overview','text','Buying the property is only the first step; effectively managing it is where the long-term wealth is secured. You must decide whether to self-manage, which saves money but costs significant time, or hire a property manager. A property manager typically charges 10-12% of the rent but handles late-night emergency calls, tenant screening, and legal compliance for you.\n\nYour relationship with the tenant is a business partnership that requires clear boundaries and mutual respect. A happy tenant who looks after your property is worth their weight in gold, saving you thousands in potential damage repairs. Conversely, a bad tenant can stop paying rent and refuse to leave, leading to costly and stressful eviction processes.',NULL,NULL,70,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.575548',NULL),(1509,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/G_XwMivTjO0',NULL,70,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.578741',NULL),(1510,3,'Key Concepts','text','Maintenance is an unavoidable part of owning physical assets, so you must budget for it before things break. The \'1% Rule\' suggests setting aside 1% of the property\'s value each year for repairs like broken boilers or leaky roofs. If you don\'t save this money monthly, a single large repair bill can wipe out your entire year\'s profit in one afternoon.\n\nCompliance with local safety laws is not optional; you are legally responsible for the safety of the people living in your building. This includes regular gas safety checks, smoke alarm testing, and ensuring the property meets energy efficiency standards. failing to do so can result in heavy fines, invalidated insurance, and even criminal charges.',NULL,NULL,70,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.581723',NULL),(1511,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the best reason.\", \"options\": [\"To pay for unexpected repairs and maintenance\", \"To buy furniture for yourself\", \"To avoid paying taxes\", \"To pay the tenant a bonus\"], \"question\": \"Why should you set aside a \'sinking fund\' from the rent?\", \"exercise_id\": 231, \"correctAnswer\": 0}',70,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.590673',NULL),(1512,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Create a \'Sinking Fund\' calculation for a hypothetical property. Metric: Estimate 10% of the monthly rent for repairs and 10% for vacancy. Question: If the property sits empty for one month a year, can you still afford the mortgage?',NULL,NULL,70,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.584086',NULL),(1513,1,'Overview','text','Due diligence is the \'detective phase\' of buying an asset, where you verify every claim the seller has made. This isn\'t just a physical inspection; it includes a financial audit to prove the rental income is real and a legal check to ensure the title is clean. Skipping this step is the fastest way to buy a \'money pit\' that bankrupts you.',NULL,NULL,71,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.799490',NULL),(1514,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/jxfGBQK3ZGk',NULL,71,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.802826',NULL),(1515,3,'Key Concepts','text','Your checklist should include verifying \'Zoning\' (can you legally use the property as intended?) and reviewing past utility bills to confirm expense estimates. Never trust the \'Pro Forma\' (projected) numbers provided by a real estate agent; always ask for the \'T-12\' (last 12 months) of actual bank statements. If a seller refuses to show their books, walk away immediately.',NULL,NULL,71,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.805792',NULL),(1516,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the reliable source.\", \"options\": [\"The seller\'s verbal promise\", \"Actual bank statements and tax returns\", \"A rough guess\", \"The real estate agent\'s brochure\"], \"question\": \"What should you rely on when verifying income?\", \"exercise_id\": 232, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',71,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.814220',NULL),(1517,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Create a 3-point checklist: 1. Physical (Roof/Structure), 2. Financial (Rent Rolls), 3. Legal (Title/Zoning). Metric: The number of documents you need to request from a seller. Question: Are you willing to lose your deposit fee to avoid buying a bad deal?',NULL,NULL,71,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.808874',NULL),(1518,1,'Overview','text','Real estate markets move in predictable cycles: Recovery, Expansion, Hypersupply, and Recession. Understanding where your local market sits in this cycle tells you whether you should be buying, selling, or waiting. Amateurs often buy at the peak of \'Hypersupply\' just before a crash, while professionals buy during the \'Recession\' phase when blood is in the streets.',NULL,NULL,72,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.967644',NULL),(1519,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/vO7-GNJIxEo',NULL,72,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.970080',NULL),(1520,3,'Key Concepts','text','Key indicators of a market peak include \'Days on Market\' increasing and inventory piling up. If houses are taking longer to sell and price cuts are becoming common, the cycle is shifting downward. Conversely, if job growth is strong and inventory is low, the market is likely in the \'Expansion\' phase, pushing prices higher.',NULL,NULL,72,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.972822',NULL),(1521,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the contrarian approach.\", \"options\": [\"When prices are at an all-time high\", \"When the market is cooling or recovering (others are fearful)\", \"When everyone else is buying in a frenzy\", \"Never\"], \"question\": \"When is typically the best time to buy real estate?\", \"exercise_id\": 233, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',72,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.984344',NULL),(1522,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check a property website for \'Price Reduced\' listings in your zip code. Metric: Count how many you see on the first page. Question: Does a high number of price cuts suggest a buyer\'s market or a seller\'s market?',NULL,NULL,72,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.976384',NULL),(1523,1,'Overview','text','BRRRR stands for Buy, Rehab, Rent, Refinance, Repeat—a strategy to build a property portfolio with limited starting capital. You buy a distressed property below market value, fix it up to increase its worth (forced appreciation), and rent it out to stabilize income. The magic happens in the \'Refinance\' step, where you pull your original cash back out based on the new, higher value.',NULL,NULL,73,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.460340',NULL),(1524,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/YEHY42zwSyo',NULL,73,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.463857',NULL),(1525,3,'Key Concepts','text','Ideally, if you bought and renovated correctly, the bank\'s refinance loan will pay off your initial purchase costs and rehab budget completely. This leaves you owning a cash-flowing rental property with $0 of your own money left in the deal. You can then take that recycled capital and \'Repeat\' the process with a new property, scaling infinitely.',NULL,NULL,73,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.467085',NULL),(1526,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"text\": \"Buy\"}, {\"id\": \"2\", \"text\": \"Rehab\"}, {\"id\": \"3\", \"text\": \"Rent\"}, {\"id\": \"4\", \"text\": \"Refinance\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"text\": \"Purchase below market value\"}, {\"id\": \"2\", \"text\": \"Fix up the property\"}, {\"id\": \"3\", \"text\": \"Place a tenant\"}, {\"id\": \"4\", \"text\": \"Pull cash out\"}], \"exercise_id\": 234}',73,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.473503',NULL),(1527,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Find a cheap \'fixer-upper\' listing. Metric: Estimate the \'After Repair Value\' (ARV) and multiply by 75% (typical refinance limit). Question: Is that number higher than the purchase price + repair costs?',NULL,NULL,73,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.469816',NULL),(1528,1,'Overview','text','Commercial real estate (offices, retail, large apartments) differs from residential because it is valued strictly on income, not comparable sales. The value is determined by the \'Net Operating Income\' (NOI) divided by the \'Cap Rate.\' This means you can force the value of the building up simply by raising rents or cutting expenses, regardless of what the neighbors\' buildings are worth.',NULL,NULL,74,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.599406',NULL),(1529,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/oLxvasjA4Wc',NULL,74,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.602968',NULL),(1530,3,'Key Concepts','text','Commercial leases are typically longer (5-10 years) and often \'Triple Net\' (NNN), meaning the tenant pays for taxes, insurance, and maintenance. This reduces the landlord\'s headache and makes the income more passive. However, the barrier to entry is higher, often requiring 30-40% down payments and a track record of experience to get financing.',NULL,NULL,74,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.605628',NULL),(1531,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the valuation method.\", \"options\": [\"By how nice the building looks\", \"By the income it generates (NOI)\", \"By the number of windows\", \"By the owner\'s opinion\"], \"question\": \"How is commercial property value primarily determined?\", \"exercise_id\": 235, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',74,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.612800',NULL),(1532,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Search for a commercial property for sale. Metric: Find the \'Cap Rate\' in the listing description (e.g., 6%). Question: Is this return higher or lower than a typical residential rental in your area?',NULL,NULL,74,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.607608',NULL),(1533,1,'Overview','text','In crypto, you are your own bank, which gives you total freedom but also total responsibility for security. Your coins live on the blockchain, but your \'Wallet\' holds the keys to move them. \'Hot wallets\' (like mobile apps) are connected to the internet and are convenient for small amounts, while \'Cold wallets\' (hardware devices) keep your keys offline and are essential for safeguarding life savings.',NULL,NULL,75,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.767741',NULL),(1534,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/2rMPSYXes6k',NULL,75,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.771053',NULL),(1535,3,'Key Concepts','text','The most critical security element is your \'Seed Phrase\'—a list of 12-24 words generated when you set up your wallet. This phrase *is* your money; anyone who has it can take your funds, and if you lose it, your funds are gone forever. Never store this phrase digitally (screenshot, email, cloud); write it on paper or stamp it in metal and hide it in a secure location.',NULL,NULL,75,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.773939',NULL),(1536,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the harsh reality.\", \"options\": [\"You lose access to your funds forever\", \"You can reset it via email\", \"The bank can restore it for you\", \"Nothing, it\'s automatically backed up\"], \"question\": \"What happens if you lose your private keys or seed phrase?\", \"exercise_id\": 236, \"correctAnswer\": 0}',75,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.781476',NULL),(1537,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Verify where your seed phrase is currently stored. Metric: Is it offline and fire-safe? Question: Who else has access to the physical location of your backup?',NULL,NULL,75,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.776212',NULL),(1538,1,'Overview','text','The irreversibility of crypto transactions makes the industry a magnet for scammers. A common tactic is the \'Giveaway Scam,\' where a fake social media account impersonating a celebrity (like Elon Musk) promises to double any crypto you send them. Remember the golden rule: if someone asks you to send money to get money back, it is 100% a scam.',NULL,NULL,76,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:30.969203',NULL),(1539,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/8pZsWn0c9g8',NULL,76,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.433103',NULL),(1540,3,'Key Concepts','text','Phishing is another major threat, where scammers send fake emails or create copycat websites to trick you into entering your seed phrase. Always bookmark your most-used exchanges and wallets to ensure you never click a malicious link from Google Ads. Never connect your wallet to a website you do not fully trust, as a malicious \'smart contract\' can drain your funds in seconds.',NULL,NULL,76,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.436028',NULL),(1541,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"rug\", \"text\": \"Rug Pull\"}, {\"id\": \"phish\", \"text\": \"Phishing\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"rug\", \"text\": \"Devs vanish with money\"}, {\"id\": \"phish\", \"text\": \"Fake links stealing info\"}], \"exercise_id\": 237}',76,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.442782',NULL),(1542,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check your email for any \'urgent\' crypto security warnings (these are usually phishing). Metric: Hover over the sender\'s address to see if it looks real. Question: Have you ever typed your seed phrase into a website?',NULL,NULL,76,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.438687',NULL),(1543,1,'Overview','text','A Decentralized Exchange (DEX) like Uniswap allows you to trade cryptocurrencies directly with other users (peer-to-peer) without an intermediary company. You simply connect your wallet, swap tokens, and the funds go straight back to your wallet. This ensures you maintain full custody of your assets at all times, protecting you from exchange bankruptcies.',NULL,NULL,77,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.981733',NULL),(1544,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/SC8KMlUi8FY',NULL,77,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.983853',NULL),(1545,3,'Key Concepts','text','Unlike centralized exchanges, DEXs do not require you to create an account or verify your identity (KYC). However, they can be harder to use and often have higher transaction fees (\'gas fees\') during busy times. You are also responsible for ensuring you are swapping the correct token, as anyone can create a fake token with a similar name to scam you.',NULL,NULL,77,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.985651',NULL),(1546,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the requirement.\", \"options\": [\"A bank account\", \"A self-custody crypto wallet\", \"A passport for ID verification\", \"A monthly subscription\"], \"question\": \"What do you need to use a DEX?\", \"exercise_id\": 238, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',77,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.993281',NULL),(1547,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Visit a DEX interface like Uniswap (no need to connect). Metric: Look at the \'Swap\' box and see the gas fee estimate. Question: Why might someone prefer paying a higher fee to use a DEX?',NULL,NULL,77,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.987632',NULL),(1548,1,'Overview','text','Many beginners mistakenly believe that crypto is tax-free or invisible to the government, but this is false. In most jurisdictions, selling crypto for fiat (cash) or trading one crypto for another (e.g., BTC for ETH) is a \'taxable event.\' You are required to report capital gains or losses on these transactions, just like selling property or stocks.',NULL,NULL,78,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.166226',NULL),(1549,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/lVSZ8Xt5sEs',NULL,78,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.169166',NULL),(1550,3,'Key Concepts','text','Keeping accurate records is your best defense. You must track the date, value, and fee of every single transaction to calculate your tax bill correctly. Using specialized crypto tax software can automate this process by connecting to your wallets and generating a tax report for you. Ignoring this can lead to audits and heavy fines years down the road.',NULL,NULL,78,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.172071',NULL),(1551,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the correct rule (general).\", \"options\": [\"Only when you withdraw to a bank\", \"Whenever you trade, spend, or sell crypto\", \"Never, crypto is tax-free\", \"When you look at the price\"], \"question\": \"When is a crypto tax event typically triggered?\", \"exercise_id\": 239, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',78,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.288481',NULL),(1552,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Log into your main exchange and find the \'Export Transaction History\' button. Metric: The number of trades you made last year (each one is a tax calculation). Question: Do you have a plan to set aside money for next year\'s tax bill?',NULL,NULL,78,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:47.174094',NULL),(1553,1,'Overview','text','A smart contract is a digital agreement written in code that automatically executes when specific conditions are met. Think of it like a vending machine: you input money + selection, and the machine releases the item without a shopkeeper needing to be present. This technology removes the need for middlemen like lawyers or banks, reducing costs and increasing speed.',NULL,NULL,79,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.557920',NULL),(1554,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/foGiA7cofEk',NULL,79,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.560827',NULL),(1555,3,'Key Concepts','text','Smart contracts run on blockchains like Ethereum and are \'immutable,\' meaning they cannot be changed once deployed. This provides certainty that the rules won\'t change, but it also means bugs in the code are permanent until a new contract is issued. They are the building blocks of Decentralized Finance (DeFi), powering everything from lending protocols to digital art marketplaces.',NULL,NULL,79,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.563222',NULL),(1556,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the best description.\", \"options\": [\"It requires a lawyer to sign\", \"It executes automatically based on code\", \"It can be easily deleted by the government\", \"It is written on paper\"], \"question\": \"What is a key feature of a smart contract?\", \"exercise_id\": 240, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',79,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.573340',NULL),(1557,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Look up the \'Etherscan\' page for a popular token like USDC. Metric: View the \'Contract\' tab to see the actual code running the token. Question: Why is \'Code is Law\' both a benefit and a risk?',NULL,NULL,79,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.565656',NULL),(1558,1,'Overview','text','Staking involves locking up your cryptocurrency to support the security of a Proof-of-Stake blockchain (like Ethereum or Solana). In exchange for validating transactions, the network pays you rewards in more coins, similar to earning interest in a savings account. It is generally considered a lower-risk way to earn passive income on your long-term holdings.',NULL,NULL,80,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.766554',NULL),(1559,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/P7Eq03O-LwI',NULL,80,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.769409',NULL),(1560,3,'Key Concepts','text','Yield Farming is a more active and complex strategy where you lend your crypto to Decentralized Exchanges (DEXs) to provide liquidity. The returns can be much higher than staking, but you face the risk of \'Impermanent Loss\'—where the value of your deposited assets drops compared to just holding them in a wallet. It requires constant monitoring and is better suited for advanced users.',NULL,NULL,80,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.772216',NULL),(1561,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"stake\", \"text\": \"Staking\"}, {\"id\": \"farm\", \"text\": \"Yield Farming\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"stake\", \"text\": \"Secures the network, lower risk\"}, {\"id\": \"farm\", \"text\": \"Provides liquidity, impermanent loss risk\"}], \"exercise_id\": 241}',80,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.779170',NULL),(1562,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Check the current staking APY (Annual Percentage Yield) for a coin you own. Metric: Compare it to the APY of a Yield Farm for the same coin. Question: Is the extra 5% yield worth the risk of Impermanent Loss?',NULL,NULL,80,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.774397',NULL),(1563,1,'Overview','text','To trade Forex effectively, you must learn to read the price chart, which is the heartbeat of the market. Most professional traders use \'Japanese Candlestick\' charts because they tell a detailed story about price action in a specific time period. A single candle shows the opening price, the closing price, and the highest and lowest points reached, giving you an instant snapshot of buyer and seller sentiment.',NULL,NULL,81,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.677338',NULL),(1564,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/zEBvX_El3LY',NULL,81,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.821618',NULL),(1565,3,'Key Concepts','text','The color of the candle indicates direction: a green (or white) candle means the price closed higher than it opened (buyers won), while a red (or black) candle means it closed lower (sellers won). The thin lines sticking out of the candle, known as \'wicks\' or \'shadows,\' show rejection. A long wick at the bottom often signals that sellers tried to push the price down, but buyers pushed it back up, suggesting a potential reversal.',NULL,NULL,81,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.824257',NULL),(1566,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the correct definition.\", \"options\": [\"The highest or lowest price reached during that time\", \"The volume of trades\", \"The opening price only\", \"The broker\'s fee\"], \"question\": \"What does a \'wick\' on a candlestick represent?\", \"exercise_id\": 242, \"correctAnswer\": 0}',81,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.832208',NULL),(1567,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Open a chart for EUR/USD on the \'Daily\' timeframe. Metric: Identify the color of the last 3 completed candles. Question: Does the sequence of colors suggest the market is currently trending up or down?',NULL,NULL,81,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.826330',NULL),(1568,1,'Overview','text','Trading is 20% strategy and 80% psychology; your biggest enemy in the market is often your own brain. The two primary emotions that destroy accounts are Fear and Greed. Fear causes you to close winning trades too early or hesitate to enter valid setups, while Greed drives you to hold losing trades too long or risk too much money on a \'sure thing.\'',NULL,NULL,82,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.969343',NULL),(1569,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/AKwifJT958o',NULL,82,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.971613',NULL),(1570,3,'Key Concepts','text','To master your psychology, you must detach your self-worth from the outcome of any single trade. A loss is not a personal failure; it is simply the cost of doing business, like buying inventory for a shop. Successful traders think in probabilities, knowing that even a perfect strategy will lose sometimes, and they remain calm because they trust their long-term edge.',NULL,NULL,82,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.973444',NULL),(1571,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the behavior to avoid.\", \"options\": [\"Trying to immediately win back money after a loss aggressively\", \"Trading against your friend\", \"Reporting a broker to the authorities\", \"A strategy used by banks\"], \"question\": \"What is \'Revenge Trading\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 243, \"correctAnswer\": 0}',82,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.980561',NULL),(1572,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Before you place your next trade, rate your emotional state on a scale of 1-10 (1 = Zen, 10 = Panicked). Metric: If you are above a 5, walk away from the screen for 10 minutes. Question: Are you trading because you see a setup, or because you are bored?',NULL,NULL,82,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:52:31.975315',NULL),(1573,1,'Overview','text','Backtesting involves applying your trading rules to historical market data to see how your strategy would have performed in the past. It gives you the statistical evidence that your strategy actually has an \'edge\' before you risk a single dollar. If a strategy didn\'t make money in the past 5 years, it is highly unlikely to make money today.\n\nTo backtest correctly, you must be honest. Don\'t \'curve fit\' by ignoring losing trades or tweaking rules to make the past look better. Scroll back on the chart, hide the future price, and go bar-by-bar, recording every trade as if it were live. This builds confidence in your system so you don\'t panic during live drawdowns.',NULL,NULL,83,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.391453',NULL),(1574,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/w4ckEZsTSjI',NULL,83,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.394512',NULL),(1575,3,'Key Concepts','text','After backtesting, you should \'Forward Test\' (or paper trade) in a demo account. Live markets have variables that backtesting misses, like spread widening, slippage, and your own emotions. Forward testing proves that you can execute the strategy in real-time under pressure.\n\nAnalyze your backtest data to find your \'Max Adverse Excursion\' (how far price usually goes against you) to optimize your Stop Loss placement. If your stops are consistently too tight, the data will show it. Use backtesting not just to prove profit, but to refine the mechanics of your entries and exits.',NULL,NULL,83,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.397325',NULL),(1576,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the correct definition.\", \"options\": [\"To predict the future perfectly\", \"To verify if a strategy has a historical edge\", \"To gamble with fake money\", \"To impress other traders\"], \"question\": \"What is the main purpose of backtesting?\", \"exercise_id\": 244, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',83,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.679909',NULL),(1577,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Open a chart and scroll back 1 year. Metric: Test your strategy on 20 trades and calculate the Win Rate. Question: Did the strategy perform well enough to trust it with real money?',NULL,NULL,83,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.399954',NULL),(1578,1,'Overview','text','Professional traders treat trading like a business, complete with operating hours and procedures. A trading routine structures your day to ensure you are analyzing the market at peak focus times, usually during the London or New York overlaps. Randomly checking charts on your phone while distracted is gambling, not trading.\n\nYour \'Pre-Market\' routine should include checking the economic news calendar, marking up key support/resistance levels, and reviewing your plan. This preparation ensures you are reactive to price, not impulsive. If you miss your pre-market prep, you should not trade that session, as you are flying blind.',NULL,NULL,84,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.940601',NULL),(1579,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/MvD7fQQ0szE',NULL,84,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.371690',NULL),(1580,3,'Key Concepts','text','Your \'Post-Market\' routine is just as vital. Once your session ends, close the charts and walk away. Sitting there staring at ticking prices leads to \'overtrading\' and decision fatigue. Use this time to log your trades in your journal and detach mentally from the market.\n\nConsistency in your routine leads to consistency in your results. By doing the same boring things every day, you reduce the emotional variance of trading. You can\'t control the market outcome, but you can control your process. A strong routine is the anchor that keeps you steady in the storm of volatility.',NULL,NULL,84,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.374118',NULL),(1581,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"pre\", \"text\": \"Pre-Market\"}, {\"id\": \"post\", \"text\": \"Post-Market\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"pre\", \"text\": \"Check Economic News\"}, {\"id\": \"post\", \"text\": \"Journal Trades\"}], \"exercise_id\": 245}',84,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.381704',NULL),(1582,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down a 3-step checklist for your Pre-Market routine (e.g., Check News, Draw Levels, Set Alerts). Metric: Time how long this routine takes (should be 15-30 mins). Question: What distraction must you eliminate during your trading block?',NULL,NULL,84,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:46.376364',NULL),(1583,1,'Overview','text','A trading journal is your most valuable mentor, providing honest feedback that no guru can give you. It involves recording every detail of every trade: entry price, exit price, strategy used, and crucially, your emotional state. By tracking your emotions, you can spot expensive patterns, like losing money every time you trade while tired or frustrated.\n\nYou cannot improve what you do not measure. Your journal will reveal your \'stats\': win rate, average risk-to-reward, and profit factor. You might discover that you are highly profitable trading EUR/USD in the morning but lose money trading Gold in the afternoon. This data allows you to cut the losing behaviors and double down on the winning ones.',NULL,NULL,85,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.949394',NULL),(1584,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/fswVPlW-njs',NULL,85,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.952983',NULL),(1585,3,'Key Concepts','text','Review your journal at the end of every week, not just when you feel like it. Look at your winning trades: did you follow your plan, or did you get lucky? Look at your losing trades: did the market just move against you (good loss), or did you break your rules (bad loss)? Differentiating between these is key to psychological growth.\n\nModern journaling software can automate the statistics, but the act of manually writing notes about your psychology is irreplaceable. It forces you to be accountable to yourself. If you are too lazy to keep a journal, you are likely too lazy to succeed as a professional trader.',NULL,NULL,85,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.955962',NULL),(1586,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the best reason.\", \"options\": [\"To write a diary for fun\", \"To identify behavioral patterns that cause losses\", \"To show your friends\", \"It is required by the government\"], \"question\": \"Why should you record your emotions in a trading journal?\", \"exercise_id\": 246, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',85,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.964983',NULL),(1587,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Log your last 3 trades (or demo trades) in a spreadsheet. Metric: Identify the \'Setup\' or reason you took the trade for each one. Question: If you had to show this log to a professional investor, would you be proud of your decisions?',NULL,NULL,85,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.959298',NULL),(1588,1,'Overview','text','A drawdown is the reduction in your account balance from a peak to a trough. Every trader, even the best in the world, experiences drawdowns; it is a mathematical certainty. The goal is not to avoid them entirely but to control their depth so they don\'t destroy your capital permanently.\n\nThe math of recovery is brutal: if you lose 50% of your account, you need a 100% gain just to get back to breakeven. If you lose 90%, you need a 900% gain. This asymmetry explains why capital preservation is the number one rule of trading. You must cut losses small so that the recovery hill doesn\'t become a mountain.',NULL,NULL,86,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.149329',NULL),(1589,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/P6s7c_w0v4c',NULL,86,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.152460',NULL),(1590,3,'Key Concepts','text','During a drawdown, your psychology is your biggest enemy. The temptation is to increase your trade size to \'win it back\' quickly, which is the fastest way to blow the account completely. The correct professional response is to *reduce* your risk per trade (e.g., from 1% to 0.5%) until you regain your confidence and rhythm.\n\nSet a \'Max Drawdown\' rule for yourself: if you lose X% of your account in a month, you stop trading until next month. This circuit breaker protects you from emotional spiral trading. Use the time off to review your journal and backtest your strategy to see if market conditions have changed.',NULL,NULL,86,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.155462',NULL),(1591,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"%\", \"prompt\": \"If you lose 50% of £1000 (left with £500), what % gain do you need on £500 to get back to £1000?\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 247, \"expected_value\": 100}',86,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.160925',NULL),(1592,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Calculate the gain required to recover from a 20% loss (Answer: 25%). Metric: Compare that to the gain required for a 50% loss (100%). Question: Why is it critical to stop a drawdown early before it compounds?',NULL,NULL,86,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:45.157611',NULL),(1593,1,'Overview','text','Money is the number one cause of relationship stress, often because partners have different \'money scripts\' from their childhoods. One might be a natural saver who views spending as dangerous, while the other is a spender who views money as a tool for enjoyment. Budgeting as a couple requires open communication to understand these underlying emotional triggers, not just the math.\n\nThere is no \'right\' way to combine finances; you can share everything, keep everything separate, or use a \'yours, mine, and ours\' hybrid model. The hybrid model is popular: a joint account for shared bills (rent, utilities) and separate personal accounts for guilt-free individual spending. The key is that both partners agree on the system and feel it is fair.',NULL,NULL,87,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.573891',NULL),(1594,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/JO9sazdQUS4',NULL,87,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.576344',NULL),(1595,3,'Key Concepts','text','Schedule a regular \'Money Date\' once a month to review your finances together over wine or coffee. Keep the tone positive and forward-looking, focusing on shared dreams like a holiday or a new home. This turns money conversations from a source of conflict into a bonding activity where you work as a team.\n\nAvoid \'financial infidelity,\' which is hiding debt or purchases from your partner. Trust is the currency of a relationship, and hiding money issues destroys that trust faster than almost anything else. Full transparency about debts and income is the baseline requirement for a healthy financial partnership.',NULL,NULL,87,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.578725',NULL),(1596,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the key to success.\", \"options\": [\"Keeping secrets\", \"Open and honest communication\", \"Earning the exact same salary\", \"Having separate houses\"], \"question\": \"What is the most important factor in couples budgeting?\", \"exercise_id\": 248, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',87,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.587693',NULL),(1597,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Schedule your first \'Money Date\' for this weekend. Metric: List 3 shared financial goals you both want to achieve in the next 5 years. Question: What is your partner\'s \'money personality\' and how does it complement yours?',NULL,NULL,87,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.581101',NULL),(1598,1,'Overview','text','While you track your budget monthly, you should review your overall financial health annually. This \'State of the Union\' for your money is the time to calculate your Net Worth, review your investment performance, and check if you are on track for long-term goals like retirement. It helps you zoom out from the daily grind and see the bigger picture.\n\nThis is also the perfect time to renegotiate your recurring contracts. spend two hours calling your insurance, internet, and phone providers to ask for a better rate or switch to a competitor. These few phone calls can save you hundreds or thousands of pounds a year with zero lifestyle change.',NULL,NULL,88,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.740960',NULL),(1599,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/WMDUful-Hp4',NULL,88,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.743543',NULL),(1600,3,'Key Concepts','text','Review your asset allocation to see if you need to \'rebalance\' your portfolio. If stocks had a great year, they might now make up 80% of your portfolio instead of your target 70%, increasing your risk. Selling some winners to buy underperforming assets forces you to \'sell high and buy low\' systematically.\n\nFinally, check your credit report and update your beneficiaries on all accounts. Life changes—marriages, births, deaths—mean that the person you listed five years ago might not be the person you want inheriting your money today. A clean administrative house prevents legal nightmares for your family later.',NULL,NULL,88,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.746165',NULL),(1601,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"You have £50k in assets and £30k in debt. What is your Net Worth?\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 249, \"expected_value\": 20000}',88,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.752566',NULL),(1602,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Calculate your Net Worth today (Assets - Liabilities). Metric: Compare it to your Net Worth from exactly one year ago. Question: Did you grow your wealth this year, and if not, what specific change will you make for next year?',NULL,NULL,88,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.748811',NULL),(1603,1,'Overview','text','Lifestyle creep, also known as lifestyle inflation, is the phenomenon where your spending rises to match your income. You get a raise, so you buy a nicer car, rent a bigger apartment, and eat at fancier restaurants. Suddenly, despite earning more money, you are still saving nothing, staying trapped in the \'rat race\' with golden handcuffs.\n\nThe danger of lifestyle creep is that it is subtle; it happens one small upgrade at a time until your new expensive life feels \'normal\' and necessary. Once you upgrade your lifestyle, it is psychologically very painful to downgrade it again. This makes you dependent on your high income, increasing your financial stress rather than lowering it.',NULL,NULL,89,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.674795',NULL),(1604,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/cI3-6moWbdU',NULL,89,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.678207',NULL),(1605,3,'Key Concepts','text','The antidote is to set a rule for every raise or bonus: save 50% and enjoy 50%. This allows you to reward yourself for your hard work while ensuring your savings rate grows alongside your income. If you double your income but also double your spending, you are no closer to financial freedom than when you started.\n\nAnother strategy is to \'pretend\' you didn\'t get the raise for the first three months. Send the entire extra amount directly to investments before it ever hits your checking account. By keeping your living expenses fixed while your income grows, you widen the gap that creates true wealth.',NULL,NULL,89,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.680933',NULL),(1606,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the definition.\", \"options\": [\"Buying a house in the suburbs\", \"Spending more just because you earn more\", \"Wearing creepy clothes\", \"Saving too much money\"], \"question\": \"What is \'Lifestyle Creep\'?\", \"exercise_id\": 250, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',89,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.691077',NULL),(1607,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Look at your last pay raise. Metric: Compare your monthly savings amount before and after that raise. Question: Did your savings increase proportionally, or did the money just disappear into \'lifestyle\'?',NULL,NULL,89,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.683108',NULL),(1608,1,'Overview','text','Value-based spending is the philosophy of spending extravagantly on the things you love and cutting costs mercilessly on the things you don\'t. Unlike traditional budgeting which asks you to cut everything, this approach asks you to prioritize. If you love travel, spend thousands on trips guilt-free, but offset it by driving a cheap car or living in a smaller flat.\n\nMost people practice \'mindless spending,\' buying a little bit of everything—medium clothes, medium car, medium food—and getting medium satisfaction. Value-based spending concentrates your financial firepower on your \'Money Dials,\' the specific areas that bring you deep joy. This maximizes the happiness-per-dollar you get from your hard-earned income.',NULL,NULL,90,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.915956',NULL),(1609,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/zD46gCj8a4g',NULL,90,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.918770',NULL),(1610,3,'Key Concepts','text','To implement this, you must be honest about what you actually care about versus what society tells you to care about. You might realize you don\'t care about fashion at all, allowing you to slash that budget to near zero without feeling deprived. This creates the surplus cash needed to fund the expensive hobbies that actually light you up.\n\nReview your bank statement to see if your spending reflects your stated values. If you say you value health but spend £200 on alcohol and £0 on the gym, your spending is out of alignment. Realigning your money with your values removes the guilt from spending and brings clarity to your financial life.',NULL,NULL,90,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.921694',NULL),(1611,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"value\", \"text\": \"Value Spending\"}, {\"id\": \"waste\", \"text\": \"Wasteful Spending\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"value\", \"text\": \"Buying a high-quality item you use daily\"}, {\"id\": \"waste\", \"text\": \"Paying for a subscription you never use\"}], \"exercise_id\": 251}',90,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.928073',NULL),(1612,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify your top \'Money Dial\' (e.g., Convenience, Travel, Food). Metric: Identify one category you can cut by 50% to fund that Money Dial. Question: How would it feel to spend *more* on what you love without worrying?',NULL,NULL,90,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.925022',NULL),(1613,1,'Overview','text','A sinking fund is a strategic way to save for large, predictable expenses by breaking them down into small monthly payments. Instead of panicking when a £600 car insurance bill arrives in December, you save £50 a month all year long. This transforms a stressful financial emergency into a boring, manageable bill payment that you are fully prepared for.\n\nYou can have multiple sinking funds for different categories: holidays, car repairs, Christmas gifts, or a new laptop. By keeping this money separate from your emergency fund, you protect your safety net for true disasters. It allows you to spend money guilt-free because you know that specific purchase has already been fully funded months in advance.',NULL,NULL,91,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.307258',NULL),(1614,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/7y2_DqW8OQs',NULL,91,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.309624',NULL),(1615,3,'Key Concepts','text','Set these funds up as separate savings pots in your banking app and automate the transfers on payday. If you know you spend £1,000 on Christmas, set up an automatic transfer of £85 a month starting in January. When December rolls around, you will have the cash ready to shop without needing to rely on credit cards or go into debt.\n\nThis strategy also works for \'fun\' goals, ensuring you don\'t sabotage your long-term wealth for short-term pleasure. If you want a luxury holiday, a sinking fund forces you to earn it slowly rather than financing it. It brings the reality of the cost into the present moment, helping you decide if it is truly worth the effort.',NULL,NULL,91,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.311826',NULL),(1616,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"You need £600 for car insurance in 12 months. How much do you save per month?\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 252, \"expected_value\": 50}',91,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.317191',NULL),(1617,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one large expense coming up in the next 6-12 months. Metric: Divide the total cost by the number of months remaining to find your monthly target. Question: Where will you keep this money so you don\'t accidentally spend it on groceries?',NULL,NULL,91,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.313704',NULL),(1618,1,'Overview','text','A \'No-Spend\' challenge is a financial detox where you commit to spending money only on absolute necessities for a set period. For a weekend, week, or even a month, you pay your rent and bills, but buy zero clothes, coffee, takeout, or entertainment. The goal is to violently reset your spending habits and break the cycle of mindless consumption.\n\nThis challenge forces you to get creative with the resources you already have, like eating the food hiding in your pantry or finding free local events. You will quickly realize how much money you usually leak on convenience and boredom. It is a shock to the system that proves you can survive—and even thrive—without constantly tapping your card.',NULL,NULL,92,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.491651',NULL),(1619,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/wfp6zKrvPok',NULL,92,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.493873',NULL),(1620,3,'Key Concepts','text','Prepare for the challenge by identifying your triggers: do you shop when you are stressed, or eat out when you are tired? During the no-spend period, you must find free alternatives to these coping mechanisms, like going for a walk or cooking a batch meal. This awareness is more valuable than the money saved because it creates lasting behavioral change.\n\nTrack your progress visually, perhaps by crossing off days on a calendar or filling a jar with the cash you would have spent. At the end of the challenge, take all the money you \'saved\' and put it directly toward a debt or savings goal. The boost in your balance provides a massive dopamine hit that motivates you to keep your spending leaner permanently.',NULL,NULL,92,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.495597',NULL),(1621,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the benefit.\", \"options\": [\"To suffer unnecessarily\", \"To reset habits and boost savings quickly\", \"To make you hate money\", \"To stop paying rent\"], \"question\": \"What is the main goal of a \'No-Spend\' challenge?\", \"exercise_id\": 253, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',92,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.504536',NULL),(1622,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Choose a timeframe (e.g., this coming weekend) for your first No-Spend challenge. Metric: Estimate how much you typically spend in that timeframe (e.g., £100 on dining/drinks). Question: What free activity will you substitute for your usual paid entertainment?',NULL,NULL,92,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.498623',NULL),(1623,1,'Overview','text','Compound interest is often called the \'eighth wonder of the world\' because of its ability to turn small sums into massive wealth over time. It works on a simple principle: you earn interest on your initial money, and then you earn interest on that interest in the following years. This snowball effect means that your money starts growing exponentially, working harder for you than you ever could for it.\n\nTime is the most critical ingredient in this formula, even more so than the amount of money you invest. A person who starts investing £200 a month at age 25 will likely have significantly more at retirement than someone who starts investing £500 a month at age 45. The biggest regret most investors have is not that they didn\'t save more, but that they didn\'t start sooner.',NULL,NULL,93,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.915872',NULL),(1624,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/wf91rEG68uq',NULL,93,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.919033',NULL),(1625,3,'Key Concepts','text','To see the real magic, you must leave the money alone and let the process happen without interruption. Every time you withdraw the interest to spend it, you reset the compounding clock and kill the momentum of your wealth. It requires patience, as the growth curve looks flat for the first few years before shooting upward vertically in the later decades.\n\nUse the \'Rule of 72\' to quickly estimate how powerful your interest rate is. Divide the number 72 by your annual interest rate to find out how many years it will take for your money to double. For example, at a 7% return, your money doubles every 10 years (72 ÷ 7 ≈ 10), meaning £10k becomes £20k, then £40k, then £80k, all without you adding a penny.',NULL,NULL,93,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.921599',NULL),(1626,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the key ingredient.\", \"options\": [\"Picking the perfect stock\", \"Time (starting early)\", \"Having a rich family\", \"Checking your account daily\"], \"question\": \"What is the most important factor in compound interest?\", \"exercise_id\": 254, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',93,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.931603',NULL),(1627,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Use an online compound interest calculator to input your current monthly savings and an 8% return rate for 30 years. Metric: Note the difference between \'Total Contributions\' (what you put in) and \'Future Value\' (what you get out). Question: Does seeing that massive \'free money\' number motivate you to stop procrastinating?',NULL,NULL,93,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.924286',NULL),(1628,1,'Overview','text','Building wealth boils down to a simple equation: accumulate assets and eliminate liabilities. In the simplest terms, an asset is something that puts money *into* your pocket, like a dividend-paying stock, a rental property, or a business. A liability is something that takes money *out* of your pocket, such as a car loan, credit card debt, or an expensive subscription.\n\nMany people struggle financially because they confuse the two, often thinking their personal home or luxury car is an asset. While your home has value, it takes money out of your pocket every month for mortgage, insurance, and repairs, making it a liability in terms of cash flow. True wealth is measured by how much income your assets generate while you sleep, not by how much stuff you own.',NULL,NULL,94,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.082878',NULL),(1629,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/JjrwZg-uXDI',NULL,94,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.085950',NULL),(1630,3,'Key Concepts','text','Rich people focus on buying assets first, then using the income from those assets to buy their luxuries. Poor and middle-class people tend to buy liabilities first, thinking they are assets, which traps them in a cycle of needing to work harder to pay for them. Before every purchase, ask yourself: \'Will this feed me, or will I have to feed it?\'\n\nYour \'Net Worth\' is the ultimate scorecard for this lesson, calculated by subtracting your total liabilities from your total assets. If you have a high income but zero assets, you are not wealthy; you are just a high-paid laborer. The goal is to shift your spending so that your asset column grows automatically every single month.',NULL,NULL,94,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.088342',NULL),(1631,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"asset\", \"text\": \"Asset\"}, {\"id\": \"liab\", \"text\": \"Liability\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"asset\", \"text\": \"Dividend Stock\"}, {\"id\": \"liab\", \"text\": \"Car Loan\"}], \"exercise_id\": 255}',94,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.095776',NULL),(1632,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Draw a T-chart with \'Assets\' on the left and \'Liabilities\' on the right, and list everything you own/owe. Metric: Calculate your current Net Worth (Total Assets - Total Liabilities). Question: What is one liability you can sell or pay off this year to improve that number?',NULL,NULL,94,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:26.091010',NULL),(1633,1,'Overview','text','A scarcity mindset operates on the belief that there is never enough—money, time, or opportunity. This fear-based thinking leads to hoarding, jealousy of others\' success, and a reluctance to invest in yourself. It traps you in a cycle of survival where you are afraid to take the calculated risks necessary for growth.\n\nAn abundance mindset, conversely, believes that money is a renewable resource and that opportunities are everywhere. When you view the world through this lens, you become generous and creative, focusing on \'how can I afford this?\' rather than \'I can\'t afford this.\' This mental shift transforms money from a source of anxiety into a tool for creation.',NULL,NULL,95,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.193741',NULL),(1634,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/F68anmvQ61o',NULL,95,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.196861',NULL),(1635,3,'Key Concepts','text','Scarcity causes tunnel vision; you become so focused on pinching pennies that you miss the dollars floating by. You might drive 20 minutes to save £2 on petrol, ignoring the value of your time. Abundance allows you to zoom out and focus on high-value activities like increasing your income or learning new skills.\n\nChanging this mindset takes practice. Celebrate when others succeed, knowing that their success proves it is possible for you too. When you spend money, do it with gratitude rather than fear, trusting in your ability to earn more. Generosity is the ultimate abundance hack; giving money away proves to your brain that you have more than enough.',NULL,NULL,95,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.199530',NULL),(1636,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the negative effect.\", \"options\": [\"It encourages smart investing\", \"It leads to fear-based decisions and hoarding\", \"It makes you generous\", \"It guarantees wealth\"], \"question\": \"How does a scarcity mindset affect financial decisions?\", \"exercise_id\": 256, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',95,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.208516',NULL),(1637,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Catch yourself saying \'I can\'t\' this week and replace it with \'How could I?\' Metric: The number of times you successfully reframe a negative financial thought. Question: Who in your life has an abundance mindset, and how can you spend more time with them?',NULL,NULL,95,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.201842',NULL),(1638,1,'Overview','text','Your brain is neuroplastic, meaning you can literally rewire your neural pathways to change how you think about money. If you grew up hearing \'money is the root of all evil,\' your subconscious will sabotage your efforts to get wealthy. You must actively overwrite these old scripts with new, empowering beliefs through repetition and emotion.\n\nAffirmations are tools to program your reticular activating system (RAS) to spot opportunities. By repeating phrases like \'I am worthy of wealth\' and visualizing your goals as already achieved, you prime your brain to act in alignment with that reality. It sounds mystical, but it is effectively just focused psychological conditioning.',NULL,NULL,96,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.379139',NULL),(1639,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/d9qSVKrnbm0',NULL,96,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.382524',NULL),(1640,3,'Key Concepts','text','You must also curate your environment to support this rewiring. If you consume news that screams about recession and hang out with friends who complain about being broke, you are reinforcing the old pathways. Feed your brain with books, podcasts, and conversations that normalize success and financial literacy.\n\nConsistency is key; you cannot go to the gym once and expect muscles, and you cannot think positively once and expect wealth. Make a daily habit of reviewing your goals and acknowledging your financial wins, no matter how small. Over time, the new abundance pathways become the path of least resistance for your brain.',NULL,NULL,96,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.385450',NULL),(1641,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"pos\", \"text\": \"Positive Script\"}, {\"id\": \"neg\", \"text\": \"Negative Script\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"pos\", \"text\": \"Money is a tool for good\"}, {\"id\": \"neg\", \"text\": \"Rich people are greedy\"}], \"exercise_id\": 257}',96,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.390844',NULL),(1642,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down three positive money affirmations and say them aloud every morning for a week. Metric: Your emotional reaction to the affirmations (do they start feeling more true?). Question: What is one negative money script you inherited from your parents?',NULL,NULL,96,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:58:44.387702',NULL),(1643,1,'Overview','text','Discipline is hard; automation is easy. The most disciplined savers don\'t rely on willpower; they rely on systems that save for them. By setting up automatic transfers from your checking to your savings account on payday, you \'pay yourself first\' before you even have the chance to spend the money.\n\nAutomation removes the emotional friction of saving. If you have to manually move money, you might hesitate or find an excuse to skip it this month. When it happens in the background, you adjust your spending to whatever is left in your account, effortlessly living within your means.',NULL,NULL,97,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.954446',NULL),(1644,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/itmujdM_7uY',NULL,97,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.957521',NULL),(1645,3,'Key Concepts','text','You can automate almost everything: bill payments, investments, and savings goals. This frees up your mental bandwidth (RAM) to focus on earning more money or enjoying your life, rather than stressing about due dates. It turns financial success into the default setting of your life.\n\nHowever, automation is not \'set it and forget it\' forever. You should review your automated flows once or twice a year, especially if your income changes. As you earn more, you must manually increase the size of your automated transfers to prevent lifestyle creep.',NULL,NULL,97,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.960401',NULL),(1646,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the best reason.\", \"options\": [\"It requires you to think about money every day\", \"It removes the temptation to spend the money before saving it\", \"It guarantees you will get rich overnight\", \"It costs money to set up\"], \"question\": \"Why is automation better than willpower?\", \"exercise_id\": 258, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',97,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.559663',NULL),(1647,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Set up one automatic transfer for savings to occur on your next payday. Metric: The percentage of your income that is now automated (aim for 5-10% to start). Question: What bills can you also put on autopay to avoid late fees forever?',NULL,NULL,97,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.962623',NULL),(1648,1,'Overview','text','Delayed gratification is the ability to resist the temptation of an immediate reward in preference for a later, larger reward. It is the muscle that allows you to drive an older car today so you can retire five years early. Every time you say \'not yet\' to a purchase, you are buying your future freedom.\n\nThe famous \'Marshmallow Test\' showed that children who could wait for a second marshmallow ended up more successful in life. In finance, the second marshmallow is compound interest. The money you don\'t spend on a gadget today can double or triple over the next decade if invested.',NULL,NULL,98,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.707774',NULL),(1649,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/H77bmcKCqq0',NULL,98,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.710751',NULL),(1650,3,'Key Concepts','text','Implement the \'72-Hour Rule\' for impulse buys: if you want something non-essential, wait 72 hours before buying it. 90% of the time, the emotional urge will fade, and you will realize you didn\'t actually need it. This simple pause creates the space for your logical brain to take over from your emotional brain.\n\nReframing is also powerful; instead of feeling deprived, feel empowered. Tell yourself, \"I am choosing to keep this money for my dream house,\" rather than \"I can\'t afford these shoes.\" This shift in language changes the feeling from restriction to strategic choice.',NULL,NULL,98,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.713321',NULL),(1651,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"You want a £100 gadget. If you invest that £100 instead at 7% return, it doubles in 10 years. How much is it worth then?\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 259, \"expected_value\": 200}',98,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.718900',NULL),(1652,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Identify one item you were planning to buy this week and delay it for 3 days. Metric: The amount of money you saved if you decide not to buy it after the wait. Question: What could that money grow into if invested instead?',NULL,NULL,98,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:25.715568',NULL),(1653,1,'Overview','text','Resilience isn\'t just mental toughness; it requires a financial shield known as an Emergency Fund. This is a stash of cash set aside strictly for true disasters—job loss, medical emergencies, or urgent home repairs. Without this fund, a single bad event can force you into high-interest debt that takes years to pay off.\n\nStart small: aim for a \'Baby Emergency Fund\' of £1,000 or one month of expenses. This small buffer solves 90% of life\'s little dramas, like a blown tyre or a broken phone, without touching your credit card. Once you are debt-free, you can expand this to cover 3–6 months of expenses for total security.',NULL,NULL,99,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.490836',NULL),(1654,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/vFJxvHpmxiw',NULL,99,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.493791',NULL),(1655,3,'Key Concepts','text','Your emergency fund must be liquid, meaning you can access it instantly without penalties. A High-Yield Savings Account is the perfect place for it, as it earns interest but is separate from your daily spending. Do not invest this money in the stock market, as you might be forced to sell during a crash when you need the cash most.\n\nHaving this money sitting \'idle\' can feel inefficient to new investors who want to maximize returns. However, the return on an emergency fund is not interest; it is insurance. It prevents you from having to sell your long-term investments at the wrong time, effectively protecting your entire portfolio.',NULL,NULL,99,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.496746',NULL),(1656,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"unit\": \"£\", \"prompt\": \"If your essential monthly expenses are £1,500, how much is a 3-month emergency fund?\", \"tolerance\": 0, \"exercise_id\": 260, \"expected_value\": 4500}',99,'numeric',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.503731',NULL),(1657,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Open a separate savings account named \'Emergency Fund\' today. Metric: The amount of money you can transfer into it right now (even £10 counts). Question: What is the smallest recurring expense you can cut to fund this account faster?',NULL,NULL,99,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.499415',NULL),(1658,1,'Overview','text','After a financial hit, the immediate reaction is often panic, followed by paralysis. The key to bouncing back is to strip your budget down to the bare bones immediately. Cut all non-essential spending—subscriptions, dining out, and hobbies—to preserve cash flow until the storm passes; you can always add the luxuries back later.\n\nCommunication is your best ally during a setback. If you cannot pay a bill, call the provider *before* the due date to explain your situation. Many companies have hardship programs or payment plans, but they can only help you if you ask. Hiding from the problem only makes the penalties worse.',NULL,NULL,100,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.679637',NULL),(1659,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/zLb3u5hX1Q0',NULL,100,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.682511',NULL),(1660,3,'Key Concepts','text','Once the bleeding has stopped, focus on income generation. This might mean taking a temporary lower-paying job, selling items you don\'t need, or freelancing. Action cures fear; the moment you start bringing in even a small amount of money, your confidence will begin to return.\n\nFinally, use the crisis as a learning opportunity to \'bulwark\' your finances against future shocks. Maybe you need a larger emergency fund, or perhaps you need to diversify your income streams. Some of the strongest financial plans are built in the ashes of a previous disaster.',NULL,NULL,100,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.685365',NULL),(1661,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the safest action.\", \"options\": [\"Continue spending as normal to keep up appearances\", \"Cut budget to bare bones immediately\", \"Take out a high-interest loan\", \"Ignore all phone calls\"], \"question\": \"What is the first step when income drops unexpectedly?\", \"exercise_id\": 261, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',100,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.695433',NULL),(1662,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: List every single subscription or recurring payment leaving your account. Metric: The total monthly savings if you paused all of them for 30 days. Question: Who is one person (friend or professional) you can trust to talk to about your situation?',NULL,NULL,100,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.687791',NULL),(1663,1,'Overview','text','A fixed mindset sees a financial loss as a permanent failure of character, leading to shame and avoidance. A growth mindset, however, views a loss as tuition paid for a valuable lesson in the school of life. If you made a bad investment or racked up debt, you haven\'t failed as a person; you have merely discovered a strategy that doesn\'t work for you. The most successful investors are not those who never lose, but those who lose, learn, and adjust course immediately.\n\nTo turn failure into growth, you must conduct a \'post-mortem\' analysis on your mistakes without judging yourself. Ask: \'What emotional trigger caused me to overspend?\' or \'Did I research this investment enough before buying?\' Identifying the root cause ensures you won\'t repeat the same error twice, turning a painful loss into a permanent asset for your future decision-making.',NULL,NULL,101,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.103813',NULL),(1664,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/oBvIYBdZG3U',NULL,101,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.106928',NULL),(1665,3,'Key Concepts','text','Many people hide their financial mistakes out of embarrassment, which prevents them from getting the help they need. Vulnerability is a strength; sharing your story with a mentor or trusted friend often reveals that they have made similar mistakes. This shared experience dissolves the shame and allows you to move forward with a clear head.\n\nRemember that your net worth is not your self-worth. You can be broke and still be a valuable, intelligent person capable of rebuilding. The graph of financial success is rarely a straight line up; it is a jagged line with dips and valleys, and your resilience in the valleys determines your ultimate peak.',NULL,NULL,101,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.109217',NULL),(1666,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"prompt\": \"Choose the healthy perspective.\", \"options\": [\"I am bad with money and always will be\", \"This loss is tuition for a valuable lesson\", \"I should hide this mistake from everyone\", \"I should give up investing\"], \"question\": \"What is the \'Growth Mindset\' approach to a financial loss?\", \"exercise_id\": 262, \"correctAnswer\": 1}',101,'multiple-choice',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.117737',NULL),(1667,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write down your biggest financial regret from the last year. Metric: List three specific things you would do differently if you faced that exact situation again today. Question: How has this mistake actually made you smarter?',NULL,NULL,101,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.111249',NULL),(1668,1,'Overview','text','It is easy to get discouraged by the slowness of progress in the early stages of building wealth. A growth mindset focuses on the trajectory, not the current position. If you are saving just £50 a month but increasing it by 1% every time you get paid, you are on a path to wealth, even if your current balance looks small.\n\nHumans are wired for instant gratification, making it hard to prioritize a retirement that is 30 years away. Visualization is a practical tool to bridge this gap; you must vividly imagine your future life to make it feel real today. Successfully visualizing your goals helps you say \'no\' to short-term temptations that don\'t align with that vision.',NULL,NULL,102,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.308450',NULL),(1669,2,'Watch & Learn','video','Watch and note 2–3 takeaways.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/EFFt7RtN8A0',NULL,102,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.311703',NULL),(1670,3,'Key Concepts','text','Create a \'Vision Board\' or a written statement that describes your ideal financial future in present-tense detail. Instead of \'I want to be rich,\' write \'I live in a paid-off home by the sea and travel four times a year.\' Specificity triggers the brain\'s problem-solving centers to find ways to make that specific reality happen.\n\nWhen the pain of discipline feels heavy, the clarity of your long-term goal lightens the load. You aren\'t depriving yourself of a purchase; you are trading a small pleasure now for a massive freedom later. Keep your vision visible—on your phone lock screen or mirror—so you never lose sight of your \'why.\'',NULL,NULL,102,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.314323',NULL),(1671,4,'Quick Check','exercise',NULL,NULL,'{\"items\": [{\"id\": \"short\", \"text\": \"Short-Term Thinking\"}, {\"id\": \"long\", \"text\": \"Long-Term Vision\"}], \"targets\": [{\"id\": \"short\", \"text\": \"Buying a car to impress friends\"}, {\"id\": \"long\", \"text\": \"Investing for freedom in 10 years\"}], \"exercise_id\": 263}',102,'drag-and-drop',1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.322681',NULL),(1672,5,'Conclusion & Next Steps','text','Action: Write a \'Letter to Your Future Self\' dated 10 years from today. Metric: The number of specific financial details (house, car, savings amount) you include. Question: What is one habit you must start today to make that letter come true?',NULL,NULL,102,NULL,1,'2025-12-15 21:55:24.317488',NULL);
